<LEADPARA>  WHEN the word "chili" is mentioned, images of tortured diners with flames
leaping from their mouths come to mind. Of course, a healthy sprinkle of
jalapenos will add an impressive tingle to most tongues. But the chili's role
in Mexican cuisine is hardly limited to culinary pyrotechnics.;   The
immensely versatile and popular chili poblano is a case in point. It has a
subtle piquancy, rich, mellow flavor and firm, meaty flesh. It can be the star
of the show, such as in a hearty chili relleno, or used as a flavoring.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MELLOW POBLANO TURNS DOWN HEAT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Ethnic Fare; See also related story on this page.; Patricia Quintana, one of
the leading experts on Mexican cooking, is the author of "Taste of Mexico" and
"Feasts of Life." Meg Rose is a New York free-lance writer.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     At its most dazzling, the stuffed poblano is dressed up in the colors of
the Mexican flag -- red, white and green -- in the dish Chiles en Nogada.
Served in this manner on Mexico's Independence Day on Monday, the chilies are
filled with a sweet ground-beef stuffing, studded with pineapple and raisins,
drenched in a creamy walnut sauce and garnished with deep red pomegranate
seeds and parsley.;   While poblanos are popular year-round in Mexico, they
literally explode onto the scene in their high season, starting in June and
peaking in September. I remember passing countless summer afternoons in the
bustling market near my home, marveling at the wondrous things the women found
to do with the poblano harvest.;   My favorite treats by far were those warm
tortilla bundles that held a delicate mixture of fresh poblanos sauteed with
onions and creme fraiche. To this day when I whip up this simple dish, it
brings back the smell and feel of my childhood summers.;   Something magical
happens to the poblano when it is dried. Not only does its name change -- the
light green variety becomes chili ancho, while the darker chili is dubbed the
chili mulatto -- but its flesh takes on a rich smoky flavor, similar to a
sun-dried tomato but with a special kick.;   Both fresh and dried poblanos are
readily available at supermarkets and produce stores in this country. However,
shopping for them can be confusing. Depending on where they are grown, the
names of these chilies vary tremendously. When cultivated in California, both
fresh and dried poblanos are referred to as chili pasilla.;   To bring out the
unique flavor of fresh poblano, it is best to roast it over the direct flame
of a gas stove or under a broiler. The traditional procedure is to char the
chili on all sides and place it in a paper bag. After "sweating" the chili for
8 to 10 minutes, peel off the thin skin and rinse the chili under a stream of
running water.;   The next important step is to devein the pepper. This means
removing the thin, lightly colored veins inside that give the chili its fire.
To do so, slit the poblano carefully along the side and remove the veins with
a sharp knife. The aroma of the chili will permeate the air, giving you an
idea of how piquant it is.;   When preparing dried poblanos -- or any dried
chili, for that matter -- it is important to rinse them thoroughly before
cooking. Mexicans traditionally dry chilies in the open air, and dust and dirt
can become trapped in the vegetable's irregular surface.;   Cooking with fresh
and dried poblanos is a great way to begin exploring the vast and varied world
of Mexican chilies.;   (hbox);   This famous dish, native to Puebla,
commemorates Independence Day. Its colors are those of the Mexican flag --
green, white and red. Though there are many ingredients, it is not a difficult
dish to make if you take it one step at a time.; CHILES EN NOGADA; (Stuffed
Chilies in Walnut Sauce);  Stuffing:; 2 tablespoons butter; 1/4 cup olive oil;
3 cloves garlic, whole, plus 3 cloves garlic, minced; 1/2 large onion, grated;
1/4 pound ground pork; 1/4 pound ground veal; 1/4 pound ground beef; 1/4 pound
ground ham; 1/4 cup raisins or currants; 1/2 cup pitted and finely chopped
prunes; 1/4 cup finely chopped candied citron; 1/4 cup finely chopped dried
apricots; 1 1/2 large fresh pears, finely chopped; 1 1/2 fresh peaches, finely
chopped; 1 apple, finely chopped; 1/2 cup finely chopped fresh pineapple; 1/4
plantain, finely chopped; 3/4 pound large tomatoes, finely chopped; 1 teaspoon
ground cinnamon;  Dash ground cloves;  Dash ground nutmeg; 2 bay leaves; 2
sprigs fresh thyme; 2 sprigs fresh marjoram; 1 1/2 teaspoons freshly ground
pepper; 1/4 cup dry sherry; 1/4 cup dry white wine;  Salt; Chilies:; 8 medium
chilies poblanos, roasted, seeded, deveined and soaked in salted water and
vinegar for 6 hours; 1/2 cup flour;  Sauce:; 1 cup shelled walnuts, soaked in
cold water overnight; 2/3 cup shelled, blanched and peeled almonds; 4 ounces
cream cheese; 2 ounces goat cheese; 1/2 cup whipping cream; 1/4 cup half and
half; 1/2 cup milk; 1 1/2 teaspoons grated onion; 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon;
2 tablespoons dry sherry;  Salt; Batter:; 5 eggs, separated; 1 1/2 teaspoons
salt; 1 1/2 tablespoons flour; 1 quart oil;  Garnish:; Seeds from 2
pomegranates; 1/4 cup chopped parsley;  To prepare stuffing, heat butter and
oil in saucepan. Add 3 whole cloves garlic and saute until brown. Discard
cloves. Add minced garlic to oil along with onion and saute until golden. Add
ground meats and saute until no longer red. Stir in raisins, prunes, citron,
apricots, pears, peaches, apples, pineapple, plantain and tomatoes. Cook until
mixture begins to thicken, about 30 minutes.;   Add cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg,
bay leaves, thyme, marjoram, pepper, sherry and wine. Season to taste with
salt. Simmer, stirring constantly, until mixture thickens, about 1 1/2 hours.
Cool. Remove bay leaves.;   Fill prepared chilies with cooled stuffing. Place
flour on piece of waxed paper. Roll stuffed chilies in flour and place on
tray. Cover and refrigerate.;   To prepare sauce, wash walnuts and peel off
skins. Grind walnuts and almonds in blender or food processor, adding cream
cheese, goat cheese, cream, half and half, milk, onion, cinnamon, sherry and
salt to taste. Mixture will be very thick. Cover and refrigerate.;   To
prepare batter, beat egg whites with a little salt until stiff. Lightly beat
egg yolks. Add yolks and flour to whites, folding in carefully.;   Meanwhile,
heat oil in deep skillet. Dip flour-coated chilies in batter, one at a time,
and fry over medium heat until golden brown. Do not crowd. Remove and drain on
paper towels. Cool to room temperature.;   To serve, place fried chilies on
platter. Ladle walnut sauce over top. Sprinkle with pomegranate seeds and
garnish with parsley. Makes 4 servings.;   Note: There may be leftover
stuffing, depending on size of chilies. It can be frozen and later used to
stuff empanadas, quesadillas, tacos or poultry.; (hbox); SALSA CON; JUGO DE
NARANJA; (Chili Salsa With Orange Juice); 1/4 cup olive oil or vegetable oil;
6 chilies anchos or dried red California or mild New Mexican chilies, washed,
seeded and deveined; 2 medium cloves garlic; 1 teaspoon salt; 3/4 cup orange
juice;  Heat oil in heavy skillet. Add chilies and stir-fry them. Process
fried chilies, garlic, salt and orange juice in blender or food processor
until blended. If salsa is too thick, add more orange juice. Makes about 1 1/2
cups salsa.  </TEXT>
