<HEAD>Who's Doing Thanksgiving This Year?</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Weston Wilson is the author of the
lifestyle cookbook ``Eating Well When You Just Can't Eat the Way
You Used To,'' Workman Publishing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JANE WESTON WILSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who's doing Thanksgiving this year?
   Is it at your children's, and are they cooking up the big bird
with all the trimmings, celebrating with their favorite foods and
introducing them to their children? Or is it just the two of you,
where a capon, duck or Cornish hen with a tasty stuffing,
vegetables, salad and a light dessert fit the bill?
   Whatever the setting or number of people, all the holiday
favorites bring back memories of this wonderful day from our own
childhoods.
   At our house, it was old-fashioned stuffing: white bread,
celery, onions and a hefty sprinkling from a yellow poultry
seasoning box with an illustrated turkey on it. A lot of stuffing
went inside me and come dinnertime, my appetite was diminished. My
grandmother always made salted cashews for holiday dinners, baked
until a burnished bronze, rubbed with brown paper to remove excess
fat, then placed in tiny silver nut dishes that I had polished. My
sister, Gerry, and I would tiptoe around the table taking a nut or
two from each dish; my hunch is the grownups were aware of the
game, but winked it away.
   It's very likely that we'll enjoy many of our favorites:
cranberry sauce, sweet potato pudding, mashed potatoes with gravy,
creamed onions, tunips, green beans, pumpkin or mincemeat pie. To
really enjoy the day, we should eat smaller portions, but not enjoy
it less.
   If you are having Thanksgiving with your family, you may want to
pitch in the next day and do something with the leftovers. Turkey
salad with fall fruits would be a delightful entree that puts the
bird in a different setting.
   If it's dinner a deux, a light, refreshing all-natural fruit ice
cream dessert leaves out the cream and eggs but doesn't change the
flavor or texture.
   And if you're taking a covered dish, turnip souffle is a part of
the traditional vegetable scene that even non-turnip fans will like.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Ceil's Turnip Souffle</NOTE>
<NOTE>Ingredients:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   2 medium yellow or 4 white turnips, peeled and chopped
   2 egg yolks, well beaten
   3 Tablespoons unsalted butter
   5 egg whites
   2 Tablespoons light or dark brown sugar, optional
   
   1. In a large saucepan over medium heat, cook the turnips in
boiling salted water to cover until tender. Drain.
   2. In a quart casserole or souffle dish, mash the turnips. Stir
in the egg yolks and butter until blended.
   3. In a medium bowl, beat the egg whites with a hand mixer until
they form stiff peaks. Slowly fold egg whites into the turnip-egg
mixture.
   4. Sprinkle surface with brown sugar, if desired.
   5. Bake in preheated 400-degree oven for 15-20 minutes or until
puffed up and lightly browned.
   6. Serve immediately.
   (Yield: 6 servings.)
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Fresh Fruit Ice Cream</NOTE>
<NOTE>Ingredients:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   1 banana, peeled and cut into thirds
   }-cup fresh or frozen strawberries
   2 Tablespoons honey or confectioners sugar
   
   1. Freeze each of the fruits separately in freezer bags 4-6
hours.
   2. Remove the bags from teh freezer about 20 minutes before
preparation.
   3. Place the banana in a food processor fitted with a metal
blade. Pulse on and off until smooth.
   4. Add the berries and puree until thick. Do not over-puree.
   5. Place in wine glasses or glass bowls. Freeze or refrigerate
until ready to serve.
   (Yield: 2 servings.)
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Turkey Salad with Apples, Pears and Pomegranates</NOTE>
<NOTE>Ingredients:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   4 cups leftover turkey, cut into 1-inch cubes
   6 ribs of celery, stringed and sliced diagonally
   1 red pepper, washed, seeded, cut lengthwise top to bottom in
{-inch slices, then cut in half
   1 green pepper, washed, seeded, cut lengthwise top to bottom in
{-inch slices, then cut in half
   1 bunch (about 5) scallions, trimmed and cut into 1-inch pieces
   2 pears, unpeeled, cored and cut lengthwise into {-inch slices
   2 apples, unpeeled, cored and cut lengthwise into {-inch slices
   1 pomegranate, seeded (toss seeds into salad)
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Dressing:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   { cup plain yogurt
   { cup mayonnaise
   { cup watercress, rinsed, patted dry, stems removed
   2 Tablespoons rice vinegar
   
   1. In a large salad bowl, mix the salad ingredients.
   2. In a blender or food processor fitted with a metal blade,
combine the yogurt, mayonnaise, watercress and vinegar until well
blended.
   3. Pour dressing over the salad, mixing lightly, combine and
refrigerate covered until serving time.
   4. Just before serving, toss the salad again and garnish with
orange slices or kumquats.
   (Yield: 6 servings.)
</TEXT>
