<LEADPARA>  SO, WHAT'S growing out on the farm that's new and exciting? At first glance,
not much.;   Unless you are a winter squash or root vegetable zealot, cold
weather produce can be challenging. It is not as flashy as
straight-off-the-vine summer produce and it's not as approachable because it
takes more effort to cook with. But, believe me, fall produce is worth the
effort, especially because of its warm earthy flavors and colors.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DELICIOUS PUMPKINS AREN'T JUST FOR FUNNY FACES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Seasonal produce; Chef Jesse Cool is co-founder of Flea Street Cafe and Late
for the Train in Menlo Park.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Burnt sienna russet potatoes, golden sugary beets, brackish green acorn
squash, crimson radishes and baby ochre carrots are beginning to replace the
final blaze of ripe tomatoes, peppers and raspberries. All are an invitation
to good fall eating, but nothing is more plentiful in October than pumpkins.; 
 Halloween sends us to the pumpkin patch for jack-o'-lanterns but, lest we
forget, pumpkins are simply a variety of winter squash -- good for the table
in more than one way. Though the big orange, carving pumpkins get all the
attention, we see more and more white ones on the market. Little Boos, with
their hard white skin, are not for cooking. They will add a festive touch to
an arrangement of Indian corn and decorative gourds that will last until
Thanksgiving.;   Those cute little miniature pumpkins also are better for
decoration than cooking because they are very difficult to cut and clean. In
addition, their flesh is not very sweet.;   Big pumpkins, with their hollow
cavities and thin lining of meat, beg to be used as attractive terrines for
soups and stews.;   To do this, cut off the top as you would for a carved
jack-o'-lantern, seed and brush the inside with oil, salt and pepper. Bake
uncovered in the oven at 350 degrees for about 30 minutes or until it is
tender when pierced with a fork. Fill with just about any piping hot
concoction and place in the middle of the table with warm corn muffins.;  
After ladling the filling into bowls, top with scoops of the tender pumpkin
flesh.;   When you visit the pumpkin patch, choose a few small ones for use in
cooking. Be sure to get cooking pumpkins rather than decorative ones. Look for
smaller ones, especially smaller Sugar Pie pumpkins. They generally weigh
between six and eight pounds.;   The meat on these (smaller pumpkins) is
delicate, sweet and purees well. Have you ever made a pumpkin pie with this
fresh pulp? It's fabulous. Follow your favorite recipe, but substitute fresh
mashed pumpkin or squash. I always leave a few lumps to add a refreshing
unrefined quality to this harvest dessert. In general, 1 pound of raw pumpkin
equals 1 1/2 to 2 cups pureed.;   Early white pumpkins are softer skinned and
have a delicate, tender, sweet flesh. Try them in a recipe that does not call
for the orange color to enhance the dish. If used in pumpkin pie, expect a
paler version.;   The remaining melange of winter squash deserves further
attention and I will do that in the Nov. 6 produce column.;   Meanwhile, there
are a few new items on the market.;   (check) Pomegranates bring back memories
of fall in Pennsylvania when my mother would give them to us as an
after-school treat. We would sit in nearby cow pastures eating them, our hands
and mouths turning magenta with juice as we spit the seeds every which way.;  
Pomegranate juice makes an extraordinary marinade. Blend the juice with garlic
and cloves and use the mixture to marinate meat or fowl. Roast the meat or
fowl with chunks of pumpkin, basting both often. Serve with couscous or rice.;
  (check) Fennel is in its prime right now, but it is a very misunderstood and
mystifying vegetable. People seem to stand at the produce stand and ponder its
use.;   Fresh fennel is a hearty vegetable. It has a mild anisette flavor and
the consistency of celery. The two can be interchanged. The smaller heads are
best used raw in salads. Larger ones roast well. Cut into big chunks, coat
with olive oil and roast at 375 degrees until soft. Braise in chicken broth
and toss with rice or risotto.;   If you're more interested in ways to use
fall produce such as pumpkin and winter squash, you might want to attend two
classes on the subject I'll be teaching at Draeger's Cooking School in Menlo
Park on Oct. 17. Call (415) 688-0688 to reserve a spot.;   Meanwhile, keep
eating those fresh string beans, tomatoes, and peppers while they last. Keep
in mind that apples are a good choice over unripe pears.;   Venture into fall,
but pay attention to your own garden and the lingering treasures of summer.;
Cool tips; (box) Get the kids to paint rather than carve faces on their
jack-o'-lanterns. They keep indefinitely if not carved and you can then
recycle them by getting the children to help you bake a real pumpkin pie when
Halloween is over.; (box) Stuff a whole pumpkin with your favorite savory
stuffing. Bake until the pumpkin is fork-tender and slice as a side dish or an
unusual vegetarian entree.; (box) Use cooked, pureed pumpkin as a thickener
for soups or stews. It adds a sweet, deep quality.; (box) Peel and cube
pumpkin, steam it and toss with pasta, sweet and hot chilies, garlic, cilantro
and olive oil. Grate Cheddar cheese over all.; (box) Thinly slice raw pumpkin
and saute with butter until tender. Splash with a bit of brandy and sprinkle
with brown sugar and serve as a side dish to crispy fried chicken.  </TEXT>
