<DESCRIPT>  USSR; TRIP; FOOD; RECIPE; MAJOR-STORY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  MENTION Russian food and many Americans envision long lines, empty store
shelves and those hapless meals of thin borscht and stringy stroganoff served
in state-run restaurants and hotels.;   But venture beyond newspaper reports
and Intourist service, and a meal in the Soviet Union can prove a culinary
voyage of discovery around the largest nation on Earth.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RUSSIAN AT THE TABLE
BEYOND BORSCHT: SOUTH, CENTRAL AREAS OFFER EXOTIC
FARE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Anya von Bremzen and John C. Welchman are the authors of "Please to The Table"
(Workman Publishing).  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Within the Soviet borders, more than 100 languages are spoken every day,
and the diversity of produce and preparations is astonishing.;   For many, the
revelations of Soviet cuisine come from the exotic, healthful foods of the
Caucasus and Central Asia, whose lush climate and cooking styles are related
to the great traditions of the Mediterranean and Middle East.;   The
picturesque Caucasian republics of Georgia, Armenia and Azerbaijan, for
example, share much with the cuisines of neighboring Turkey and Iran -- arrays
of stuffed vegetables, bulgur and rice pilafs, meat grilled on skewers,
eggplant in a thousand disguises, egg and lemon or garlicky yogurt sauces, and
sinful honey and nut-based sweets perfumed with rosewater.;   Yet, as
everywhere in the USSR, their cooks work with flair and distinction. While the
Georgians work wonders with walnuts, the Armenians prefer pine nuts and
almonds. Cilantro is the herb of choice in Georgia, but the Azerbaijanis adore
mint and tarragon, which they wrap in flatbreads along with a slice of feta
cheese for a casual snack. All of the Caucasian republics are devoted to
spices, but the favorites are cumin, allspice, cinnamon and mild chilies in
Armenia; coriander, hot chilies and fenugreek in Georgia; and turmeric and
saffron in Azerbaijan.;   In the tiny western nation of Moldova there is a
delightfully diverse Balkan-style cuisine. Corn is the main staple, and
mamaligha, a cornmeal mush much like Italian polenta, accompanies almost every
meal. If mamaligha doesn't make the daily menu, then a savory, feta-flavored
corn bread is sure to appear. This bread is at its best accompanied by a
beautifully textured vegetable caviar called givech, or by roasted red
peppers. Other regional temptations include bountiful moussakas, feta-stuffed
peppers and a profusion of sweet and savory strudels.;   This is a land of
plenty. On a recent trip to the Uzbek and Kazakh republics in Soviet Central
Asia, even in the winter, there was no sign of the lines and distribution
problems that afflict the colder northern areas of the USSR.;   The modern
Olai bazaar in the Uzbek capital, Tashkent, was ablaze with piles of bright
orange and yellow carrots, carefully julienned and mounded into spectacular
heaps on the white-slabbed counters. Nearby were baseball-size green radishes,
purple-tinted garlics and piles of ripe pomegranates sliced through to expose
their sparkling crimson seeds. The region's yellow carrots lend the Uzbek's
favorite lamb pilaf a delicious mild sweetness punctuated by a skillful blend
of spices -- cumin, hot and sweet ground chilies and barbaris (a tart purple
berry).;   Here and there were fast-food joints selling perfect lamb-filled
steamed dumplings (borrowed from neighboring China; steaming is one of the
preferred cooking methods in Central Asia), and savory, filled pastries called
samsa -- not dissimilar to the Indian samosas from which they take their name.
Among other culinary debts to India were the stacks of warm "non" flatbreads
baked in outdoor clay ovens, and the many mung bean dishes so popular in both
regions.;   Soviet cuisine is probably the most diverse in the world, and as
the USSR emerges from its momentous social and economic changes, food lovers
everywhere will be fascinated to encounter its wide world of cuisine.;   This
version of a Georgian recipe makes a great buffet dish and is a real treat for
those who love crispy baby vegetables. The sauce also works well as a dip with
raw vegetables.; COLD STEAMED VEGETABLES WITH WALNUT SAUCE; (POSTNEULI
NIGVZIS; SOTSIBELIT);  Walnut Sauce:; 3/4 cup walnut pieces; 2 large cloves
garlic; 1/2 small dried chili pepper, seeded; 6 small sprigs cilantro; 1/8
teaspoon coarse (kosher) salt; 1 1/4 cups chicken stock;  Small pinch saffron
threads, crushed in a mortar and diluted in 1 tablespoon warm water; 1/4
teaspoon sweet Hungarian paprika; 1/4 teaspoon ground coriander; 1/8 teaspoon
ground fenugreek; 1 tablespoon red wine vinegar;  Vegetables:; 1 1/2 pounds
mixed vegetables (such as small new potatoes, baby carrots, asparagus, green
beans, cauliflower florets, wax beans);  Salt, freshly ground pepper;  To make
sauce, process walnuts, garlic, chili pepper, cilantro and salt in food
processor until pulverized. Transfer to medium saucepan and add chicken stock.
Slowly bring to simmer, stirring. Add saffron, paprika, coriander, fenugreek
and more salt if needed. Cook, stirring, without allowing mixture to boil, 3
to 4 minutes. Remove from heat and stir in vinegar. Cool, cover and
refrigerate until ready to use.;   Fill large pan with 2 inches salted water
and fit with steamer basket. Bring water to boil and steam each vegetable
separately to desired doneness. Refresh under cold running water. Drain well
and pat dry with paper towels. Refrigerate, covered, until ready to use, but
no more than 1 day.;   To serve, place bowl with walnut sauce in center of
serving platter. Arrange vegetables attractively around bowl. Makes 8
servings.; (hbox); This is a potato soup to top all potato soups. Thick and
creamy, it has the woodsy aroma of wild mushrooms enlivened by bacon
cracklings and paprika.; LATVIAN POTATO; AND WILD MUSHROOM SOUP; (KARTOFELNY
SUP S GRIBAMI); 1 ounce imported, well-rinsed dried wild mushrooms (such as
Polish, porcini or cepes); 5 1/2 cups water;  Salt; 6 medium russet potatoes,
peeled and cubed; 4 slices bacon, finely diced; 1 small onion, finely chopped;
2/3 cup whipping cream;  Sweet Hungarian paprika;  Freshly ground pepper; 
Chopped fresh dill for garnish;  Soak mushrooms in 1 cup of the water 2 hours.
Drain and strain liquid through coffee filter. Bring mushrooms, their soaking
liquid and remaining 4 1/2 cups water to boil in large soup pot over high
heat. Add salt. Reduce heat to low and simmer, covered, 30 minutes.;   Add
potatoes. Increase heat to medium-low and cook 15 to 20 minutes, or until
potatoes are tender. Remove from heat. Remove mushrooms with slotted spoon.
When cool enough to handle, chop them very fine.;   Using slotted spoon,
transfer potatoes to food processor. Add 1 cup cooking liquid and process
until pureed. Whisk potatoes back into cooking liquid in pan. Stir thoroughly
with fork or wire whisk until there are no lumps. Set aside.;   Saute bacon in
small skillet until it renders its fat. Drain off all but 1 tablespoon fat,
then add onions and mushrooms. Saute, stirring occasionally, over medium-high
heat until mixture is well browned, about 15 minutes.;   Return soup to low
heat. Add cream and simmer gently 2 minutes, until soup is about to boil. Stir
in sauteed onion-mushroom-and-bacon mixture. Season to taste with few dashes
paprika, salt and pepper. Simmer an additional 3 to 4 minutes. Serve garnished
with fresh dill. Makes 6 servings.; (hbox); This bread is excellent with stews
and soups, or with just a slice of feta cheese or smoked ham, as it is often
enjoyed in Moldavia. It is a very savory corn bread, indeed.;   MOLDAVIAN CORN
AND FETA CHEESE BREAD; (KUKURUZNIY KHLEB S BRINZOY); 3 cups crumbled feta
cheese; 1/2 cup sour cream; 2 large eggs, lightly beaten; 2 cups milk; 6
tablespoons unsalted butter, melted; 2 cups yellow cornmeal, preferably stone
ground; 3/4 cup unbleached flour; 1/2 teaspoon sugar; 2 teaspoons baking
powder; 1/2 teaspoon baking soda;  Stir together feta cheese, sour cream,
eggs, milk and melted butter in large bowl.;   Sift together cornmeal, flour,
sugar, baking powder and baking soda and stir into feta mixture. Blend
thoroughly. Cover and let stand 15 minutes.;   Transfer batter to buttered
13-by-9-inch baking dish. Bake on middle rack at 375 degrees until light
golden brown and firm to the touch, 35 to 40 minutes. Serve warm. Makes 6 to 8
servings.;   (hbox); Serve this dish with a tomato, onion and pepper salad.;
CENTRAL ASIAN LAMB PILAF WITH GARBANZO BEANS; AND RAISINS; 1/2 cup light oil;
2 pounds lamb shoulder, cut into 2-inch pieces; 1 pound carrots, julienned; 2
cups chopped onions;  Salt; 2 teaspoons imported sweet paprika; 1/2 teaspoon
imported hot paprika; 1/2 teaspoon turmeric; 2 teaspoons whole cumin; 1
(16-ounce) can garbanzo beans, well-drained; 3/4 cup dark raisins; 2 medium
heads garlic, outer layer of peel removed, but not divided into cloves; 2 1/2
cups long-grain rice; 5 cups boiling chicken stock;  Heat oil in large,
cast-iron pan over medium-high heat. Add lamb and cook a few pieces at a time
until well browned. With slotted spoon, transfer lamb to bowl.;   Add carrots
and onions and cook, stirring, about 8 minutes. Return lamb to pan. Season to
taste with salt, add paprikas, turmeric and cumin and stir well. Reduce heat
to low and cook, stirring occasionally, until lamb is almost tender, about 45
minutes.;   Stir in garbanzo beans, raisins and garlic. Add rice without
mixing it into lamb mixture. Add boiling stock in slow stream. Increase heat
to high. Bring to boil and boil 3 minutes. Adjust salt to taste. Reduce heat
to low. Cover and simmer until liquid is absorbed and rice is tender, about 20
minutes. Remove from heat and let stand, covered, 10 minutes.;   Transfer rice
to large platter, fluffing it with fork. Arrange lamb mixture in a mound on
top of rice, topping with garlic heads. Makes 6 servings.  </TEXT>
