<HEAD>Exotic Vegetables Catching On In American Supermarkets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bok choy and escarole aren't crops for every
farmer, but an Agriculture Department economist says such exotic
food items are catching the eye of supermarket shoppers.
   Increasingly, produce counters are also including fruits that are
a bit off the trodden path of consumers: pomegranates, guava,
kumquats, and melons named Santa Clause, Casaba and Crenshaw.
   ``Specialty fruit and vegetable displays form a fundamental part
of the new up-scale image of many produce sections,'' said Catherine
Greene of the department's Economic Research Service.
   Rising demand for specialty produce is in line with a general
increase in fruit and vegetable consumption, she said. The average
American consumed 427 pounds of fruits and vegetables last year, up
12 percent since 1972. That is a farm weight equivalent before
trimming, processing and after-harvest losses, she said Wednesday.
   Greene said the per capita trend is expected to continue upward,
although there could be some year-to-year variations. For example,
she said, this year's drought probably will cause some decline from
the 1987 average.
   In any case, specialty fruits and vegetables are the rage among
many consumers, and there is no sign the demand will taper off soon.
Greene, writing in the agency's National Food Review, said there are
a number of reasons.
   ``Americans have become more health conscious, eating lots of
fruits and vegetables as part of a well-balanced diet,'' she said.
``Consequently, we want a huge selection of produce.''
   Further, Americans travel more frequently than they used to, and
many want ``foreign'' foods when they return home.
   ``Unusual fruits and vegetables are appearing on restaurant
menus,'' Greene said. ``Also influencing our diets are recent
immigrants from the Caribbean, Central America and Southeast Asia
who have brought their native foods with them.''
   A recent survey by the industry's Food Marketing Institute showed
that the number of items sold in supermarket produce departments
more than doubled to 150 between the mid-1970s and the early 1980s.
Today, more than 250 items is the norm, including new packs and
sizes of traditional fruits and vegetables, along with exotic and
specialty produce.
   Another survey conducted for a trade journal, The Packer, showed
the most frequently tried specialty fresh vegetables were alfalfa
and bean sprouts, followed by snow peas, pearl onions, parsnips,
leeks, baby vegetables, Chinese cabbage and shallots.
   Moreover, about a third of those surveyed also had seen or heard
of less widely known specialty vegetables such as Belgian endive,
bok choy, celeriac, daikon, kohlrabi, parsley root and Jerusalem
artichoke.
   The most frequently tried specialty fresh fruits, in order, were
pomegranates, persimmons, kumquats, quince and guavas.
   Additionally, at least a third of those surveyed had seen or
heard of breadfuit, passion fruit, plantains, prickly pear and red
bananas. But some fruits were nearly unkown: Asian pears,
carambolas, cherimoyas, sapotes, radiccho and rappini.
   Greene said the survey showed that consumers in the western
United States are more likely to try specialty produce and fresh
herbs, another group of growth items. One factor is the West's large
Asian and Hispanic populations, with their interests in exotic
produce.
   Also, it was shown that consumers in the upper income brackets
eat more of the speciality fruits and vegetables.
   ``They may be better informed about the variety of produce
available and better able to afford the premium prices that
specialities sometimes command,'' Greene said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the value of
U.S. agricultural exports jumped 26 percent to a four-year high of
$35.2 billion in the fiscal year that ended on Sept. 30.
   Actual quantities of grain and other commodities totaled 147.5
million metric tons, up 14 percent from 129.2 million tons shipped
in 1986-87 when the value was $27.9 billion.
   The new figures released Wednesday were up from the previous
forecast issued on Aug. 25, when the value was projected at $34
billion and the volume at 146 million tons.
   Despite the sharp gains, the year's totals were still far below
the record levels of $43.8 billion and 162.3 million tons in 1980-81
before world economic conditions, high interest rates, foreign
competition and other economic factors triggered annual declines.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers credited the 1985 farm law's
lower price support mechanisms with making U.S. commodities more
competitive in world trade.
   Myers said a decline in food prices last month ``proves that
export increases did not occur at the expense of U.S. consumers,
despite this summer's damaging drought.''
   The USDA says higher commodity prices point to another increase
in the value of exports in the fiscal year that began on Oct. 1. But
it says the actual volume may decline.
   A forecast of 1989 farm exports is scheduled for release on Nov.
29.
   Wheat accounted for two-thirds of the volume increase last fiscal
year, and ``significant increases'' were reported for corn,
livestock feed and fodder, and vegetable oils.
   Overall, exports of grains and feeds accounted for more than
$12.7 billion of the total, up 37 percent.
   Other categories included: oilseeds and products, $7.7 billion,
up 19 percent; livestock products, $4.9 billion, up 24 percent;
horticultural products, $3.8 billion, up 21 percent; cotton, $2.15
billion, up 50 percent; and tobacco, $1.3 billion, up 8 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's drought-reduced grain and soybean
harvests will mean sharply higher feed costs for livestock producers
in the coming year, with some items costing almost half again as
much, says the Agriculture Department.
   Drought and hot weather reduced total feed grain production by 34
percent this year to the smallest total since 1983.
   Prices of feed grains, mostly corn, are expected to average 25
percent to 45 percent above last year's weighted average of $76.70
per ton, the department's Economic Research Service said Wednesday.
Soybean meal prices may average $235 to $275 per ton, compared with
$222 in 1987-88.
</TEXT>
