<DESCRIPT>  FRUIT; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN I was looking for a quick, easy dessert that was also low in fat, fruit
compotes naturally came to mind. These refreshing treats appeared often on the
table during my childhood, and were second only to my mother's homemade cakes
as my dessert of choice.;    Compote, another word for poached fruit, can be
made from fresh or dried fruit or a mixture of both. At elegant restaurants,
it is served in a stemmed dessert dish called a compotier.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  POACHING SYRUP TURNS FRESH OR DRIED FRUIT
INTO DELICIOUSLY WARM DESSERT
COMPOTES: EASY AND ELEGANT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cook It Quick
Faye Levy is the author of the three-volume "Fresh from France" cookbook
series, published by E.P. Dutton, and of "Sensational Pasta," published by HP
Books.)  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The classic poaching syrup is made of sugar and water and scented with a
vanilla bean. For dried fruit and pears, the syrup is often made with red
wine, which imparts a wonderful color and flavor to the fruit. Port, Madeira,
sherry, sweet white wine or apple cider can replace half the water in the
syrup. Honey or maple syrup are sometimes substituted for the sugar.;    If
you prefer zesty desserts, there is a wide range of spices and other aromatic
flavorings you can add to the syrup such as lemon or orange peel and juice,
cinnamon sticks and cloves, fresh ginger, allspice berries, aniseed or even
black or white peppercorns.;    Since compote is a light dessert, it is
perfect after a copious meal. It involves little work, can be made ahead and
is ready in minutes.;    Compote is served warm or cold with a few tablespoons
of the syrup. If you like a more sauce-like syrup, you can boil it down or can
thicken it further with a few tablespoons of jelly. At serving time, a splash
of Grand Marnier, Calvados (apple brandy) or pear brandy gives the fruit
sparkle.;    Offer compote as a refreshing accompaniment for angel food or
pound cake. Serve warm fruit compote over pancakes or waffles for brunch. For
a fast fruit crumble, sprinkle apple or pear compote with granola, warm it
briefly in the oven and top it with scoops of vanilla ice cream.;    (hbox);  
 If you like baked apples, you will appreciate this apple compote, which cooks
much faster. Serve the compote on its own or topped with whipped cream or
vanilla ice cream. If any syrup is left over, you can use it to poach more
fruit or as a light sauce for ice cream. If vanilla beans are not available,
or for a different taste, substitute 1 cinnamon stick.;     VANILLA-SCENTED
APPLE COMPOTE;  3/4 cup sugar; 3 cups water; 1 vanilla bean;  Zest of 1 lemon
or 1 orange, removed with a vegetable peeler, optional; 1 to 1 1/4 pounds
golden delicious or Granny Smith apples (3 or 4 medium); 1 tablespoon lemon
juice;   Combine sugar, water, vanilla bean and lemon zest in medium saucepan.
Bring to boil, stirring gently to dissolve sugar. Remove from heat.;    Peel
apples, halve and remove cores. Cut each half in two. Return syrup to boil and
add apple quarters and lemon juice. Reduce heat to low. Cover with lid that is
a bit too small for saucepan to keep apples submerged. Cook 8 to 12 minutes or
until apples are very tender when pierced with point of knife.;    For thicker
syrup, remove apples and simmer syrup a few minutes or until thickened to
taste. Let apples cool in syrup. Serve warm, at room temperature or cold.
(Apples can be kept in syrup about 4 days in refrigerator.) Makes 4 servings.;
   Pear compote: Peel 1 1/2 pounds ripe, but fairly firm, pears and rub them
well with cut side of lemon half. Halve pears and remove cores. Poach about 12
minutes. For pears in red wine, substitute dry red wine for the water -- in
this case there is no need to rub peeled pears with lemon.;    Pineapple
compote: Increase sugar to 1 cup and water to 3 1/3 cups. Peel 4-pound
pineapple and cut crosswise in 1/2-inch-thick slices. Cook 8 minutes or until
slices are tender at edges.; (hbox);    Prunes are the best fruit for
preparing this way, but a package of mixed dried fruit gives the dessert a
variety of colors and textures.;     DRIED FRUIT COMPOTE WITH RED WINE; 1
pound pitted prunes or mixed dried fruit; 1 bottle (3 cups) dry red or white
wine;  1/2 to 1 cup water; 1 cinnamon stick; 1 bay leaf, optional;  Zest of 1
lemon or 1 orange, removed with vegetable peeler, optional;  1/2 cup sugar;  
Combine fruit and wine in saucepan and add enough water to barely cover. Add
cinnamon stick, bay leaf and lemon zest. Sprinkle mixture with sugar. Gently
stir over low heat to dissolve sugar. Cover and cook over low heat 20 to 30
minutes or until tender. Transfer to bowl and let cool, spooning wine over
fruit from time to time. Serve cold. (Fruit can be kept, covered, 2 weeks in
refrigerator.) Makes 6 to 8 servings.; (hbox);    This easy, elegant dessert
combines poached fruit with a quick berry sauce made from the poaching syrup
and frozen berries. If you like, top each portion with a scoop of vanilla ice
cream and spoon a little sauce over it.;     FRUIT COMPOTE WITH BERRY SAUCE; 
Apple, pear or pineapple compote (recipe above), with 1/4 cup of its syrup; 1
(10- to 12-ounce) package frozen unsweetened or lightly sweetened
strawberries, raspberries or blackberries, thawed; 3 tablespoons syrup from
compote; 3 or 4 tablespoons powdered sugar or to taste; 1 to 2 tablespoons
lemon juice, optional;  Fresh mint sprigs for garnish, optional;   Prepare and
cool compote. Puree thawed berries with 3 tablespoons syrup from compote in
food processor or blender. If using raspberries or blackberries, strain sauce,
pressing on puree so seeds remain in strainer. Sift powdered sugar into sauce
and mix well. Taste and add more syrup, powdered sugar or lemon juice to
taste.;    Spoon fruit pieces into 4 dessert dishes and spoon over a little
sauce or make a bed of sauce and spoon fruit pieces on top. Garnish with mint.
Serve remaining sauce separately. Makes 4 servings.  </TEXT>
