<LEADPARA>  Profession: Executive chef, San Jose Athletic Club.;    Background: Born in
Shiraz, Iran, where his family owned fruit orchards and a farm. There, he fed
the hired help and soon expanded his cooking to include catering weddings.
Came to America in 1974 with the aid and encouragement of some San Joaquin
Valley growers with whom he had done business.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BEN ZARE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Connoisseur
Four Star
Food favorites of celebrity gourmets  </MEMO>
<TEXT>    After a year in Miami, where he worked in restaurants and took food service
courses, he came to Santa Cruz to be closer to friends. He continued to work
in restaurants and study food service in Santa Cruz, then Salinas, and then
Fresno, where he opened his first restaurant called The Cage. In 1986, he
became a chef at Chaminade in Santa Cruz.;   When the San Jose Athletic Club
came under new management in January 1990, he was named executive chef. The
club has private membership, but the dining room is open to the public for
lunch.;    Style of cooking: California cuisine with seasonings from around
the world, especially Persia and India. "I can't just cook Persian or Indian
dishes because people won't eat them. But if I give the dishes a different
name and don't tell people what's in them, they usually like them.";   
Marital status: Married 10 years. He and wife Linda have two children,
Shamila, 6, and Layla, 3 months.;    Home: A three-bedroom house in Soquel
with a large herb and vegetable garden.;    Age: 40;    Relaxation: Reading
Persian poetry, especially the works of Khayyam,, Hafez and Saadi. "It helps
to give my life focus. I read while I'm doing the laundry at home.";   
Hobbies: Gardening and soccer. He plays soccer twice a week at Mission College
with a group of "over 35 guys.";    Favorite restaurant: King Chuan in Santa
Cruz.;    Favorite movie: "Dances with Wolves";    Car: Blue 1989 Honda Civic
and a blue 1989 Toyota pickup.;    Heroes: Joe Montana. "I liked the fact that
no matter how many times he got knocked down, he always got up and kept moving
toward his goal. As a soccer fan, I never watched football. Now I only watch
49ers' games.";    Proudest moment: When people tell him that he's doing a
good job.;    If you could have one last meal, it would be: A Persian
specialty of duck with pomegranate sauce.;    Describe yourself: "Sensitive. I
enjoy helping other people. I often put others' needs ahead of mine. I also
will do whatever it takes to succeed, because I know I'll eventually be
rewarded.";    Plans: To become the executive chef of Western Athletic Clubs,
the company that manages a number of athletic clubs on the West Coast,
including the San Jose Athletic Club.;    Favorite recipe; BAKED PRAWNS WITH
GOAT CHEESE;  1 pound prawns (16-20 count, if possible);  1/4 cup olive oil; 
1 small onion, sliced;  2 to 3 cloves garlic, crushed;  1/3 cup chopped green
onions or chives;  1 1/2 cups peeled tomatoes, chopped;  1/4 cup dry white
wine;  1/2 tablespoon fresh oregano, chopped;   Salt and pepper to taste;  2
to 3 ounces goat or lamb cheese, such as feta;  1 tablespoon chopped parsley; 
 Shell and devein prawns, but leave tails on. Rinse and pat dry with paper
towels. Gently saute onion in oil in a skillet until onion is transparent. Add
garlic and half the green onions. Cook 2 minutes longer. Add tomatoes, wine,
salt and pepper; cover and simmer 20 minutes until sauce thickens.;    Spoon
half the sauce into a baking dish. Add oregano, remaining green onions and
prawns. Add remaining sauce, top with crumbled goat cheese. Bake in 375 degree
oven 8 to 12 minutes or until prawns are pink and cheese is melted and lightly
browned. Sprinkle with parsley and serve as an appetizer with flat bread or as
an entree with rice or pasta Serves 5 as an appetizer, 3 to 4 as an entree.  </TEXT>
