<LEADPARA>  Traditional food for Rosh Hashana, which begins at sundown Sept. 8, varies by
region. But the theme of sweetness and joy for the New Year unites Jewish
celebrants around the world. Foods frequently served include honey, apples,
dates, quinces, pomegranates, leeks, Swiss chard, green beans, carrots,
turnips, zucchini, lamb and fish, according to Alain Levy, chef at the
Culinary Institute of America. Levy says it is customary before the meal to
dip a piece of apple in honey and wish for the coming year to be just as
sweet. Honey stands for the sweetness of the year ahead; stuffed foods for
abundance; the leek for good luck; fish for fertility, among other happy
aspects of life.;  LAMB WITH VEGETABLES  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JEWISH TABLE
FOR A 'GOOD AND SWEET'
YEAR, CHEF AND COOKBOOK
AUTHOR SHARE THEIR ROSH
HASHANA RECIPES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   3 pounds lamb shoulder, cubed;  Salt and pepper to taste;  Pinch saffron; 2
pounds onions, peeled and sliced;  Juice of 1 lemon; 2 tablespoons sugar; 
Pinch cinnamon; 1 pound turnip, peeled and diced; 1/2 pound zucchini, skin
removed, diced; 1/2 pound pumpkin, skin removed, diced;  Place lamb pieces in
a casserole. Add salt, pepper, saffron, onion and cold water to cover. Simmer
until meat is tender, about 1 1/2 to 2 hours. Remove meat and keep warm.;  
Adjust seasoning of broth with salt and pepper. Add lemon juice, sugar and
cinnamon; simmer for 10 minutes. Add vegetables and continue to simmer until
tender, about 10 minutes. Return meat to pan to reheat before serving. Makes 6
servings.;   -- Alain Levy, chef, Culinary; Institute of America;  BEEF
BRISKET WITH POTATOES AND PRUNE TZIMMES; 2 pounds fresh beef brisket;  Salt
and pepper to taste; 2 pounds medium potatoes, peeled; 1/4 cup vegetable oil;
1/4 cup flour; 1 pound pitted prunes; 1/4 cup sugar;  Juice of 1/2 lemon; 
Season brisket with salt and pepper and refrigerate for 2 hours. Place brisket
in a pot and add cold water to cover. Bring to a simmer and cook for 1 1/2
hours. Add potatoes and continue cooking 30 minutes. Transfer meat and
potatoes to a roasting pan. Reserve 2 cups of liquid.;   Heat oil in a
saucepan. Add flour and stir until smooth. Gradually add reserved liquid,
stirring constantly until thick and smooth. Adjust seasoning with salt and
pepper; add prunes, sugar and lemon juice.;   Pour gravy over meat and
potatoes in the roasting pan. Bake in a 350-degree oven until brown, about 30
minutes. Slice meat across grain and serve with gravy and prunes. Makes 6
servings.;   -- Alain Levy, chef, Culinary; Institute of America;  CARROT
TZIMMES; 2 pounds carrots, peeled and sliced;  Pinch salt; 1/4 cup honey; 
Juice of 1/2 lemon; 1/4 cup vegetable oil; 1/4 cup flour;  Place carrots in a
heavy saucepan and add cold water to cover. Bring to a simmer and cook until
carrots are almost tender. Add salt, honey and lemon juice; simmer for 20
minutes.;   In another saucepan, heat oil. Add flour and blend. Add carrots
and cooking liquid; simmer, stirring constantly, until thickened. Brown
lightly under the broiler before serving. Makes 6 servings.;   -- Alain Levy,
chef, Culinary; Institute of America; YAM AND CABBAGE TZIMMES; 1 teaspoon
margarine; 2 cups shredded savoy cabbage, about 1 small head; 2 large yams
(about 1 1/2 pounds) peeled, halved, then thin-sliced; 2 sweet medium apples,
peeled, cored and coarsely chopped; 15 pitted prunes, halved; 3 tablespoons
frozen apple juice concentrate; 1/4 cup firmly packed light or dark brown
sugar; 1/2 cup sweet Passover wine (cherry or grape concord); 1 teaspoon
ground cinnamon; 1/2 teaspoon ground ginger; 1/2 teaspoon ground cardamom; 2
tablespoons honey; 2 teaspoons margarine, cut into small pieces;  Preheat oven
to 375 degrees. Grease a 9-by-11-inch oven-proof casserole with 1 teaspoon
margarine. Arrange cabbage, yams, apples and prunes in layers, using one-half
of each ingredient for each layer.;   In a bowl, combine and blend apple juice
concentrate, sugar, wine, spices and honey. Spoon evenly over vegetable
mixture. Dot with remaining 2 teaspoons margarine. Cover with a sheet of
aluminum foil. Bake in a 375-degree oven for 1 hour. Uncover and gently stir.
Loosely cover and return to the oven for 15 minutes. Makes 8 servings.;  
Note: This dish may be prepared well ahead of serving time, covered and
reheated.;   -- From "Francine Prince's; New Jewish Cuisine" (G.P.; Putnam's
Sons, $22.95);  FIG AND DATE CAKE; 10 ounces dried figs (about 22 small figs),
stems cut away, each fig halved; 8 ounces dried pitted dates (about 35
standard-size dates), each date halved; 1/2 cup whole shelled almonds; 1/4 cup
granulated sugar; 2 large eggs (use 1 yolk and 2 whites); 1/2 cup corn oil or
safflower oil; 1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla extract; 1 1/4 cups unsweetened apple
juice; 1/2 cup firmly packed dark brown sugar; 2 tablespoons dark honey, such
as buckwheat; 2 1/4 cups unbleached flour; 6 tablespoons oat bran; 1/2
teaspoon salt; 1 tablespoon baking soda; 1/2 teaspoon ground ginger; 1/2
teaspoon ground cardamom; 1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon; 1/2 cup dark seedless
raisins;  Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Fit large food processor with steel
blade. Put figs, dates, almonds and granulated sugar into the work bowl of the
processor. Process with six on-off turns.;   In a cup combine eggs, oil and
vanilla; blend with a fork. In a small saucepan, combine apple juice, brown
sugar and honey; stir. Barely warm until sugar and honey dissolve. With
processor running, pour egg mixture through feed tube, then immediately pour
apple juice mixture through tube. Stop machine.;   In a bowl, combine flour
with bran, salt, baking soda and spices. Remove the cover of processor and add
half the dry ingredients. Process for 4 seconds. Repeat procedure with
remaining dry ingredients. Remove work bowl from base of food processor. With
a rubber spatula, stir in raisins. Pull out blade, scraping off clinging
batter.;   Grease two 8-inch loaf pans with margarine. Divide dough between
pans, smoothing out tops. Bake in center section of a 350-degree oven for 50
to 55 minutes. Loaves are fully baked when cake moves away from the sides of
pans, and when a toothpick inserted into centers comes out dry. Place pans on
wire rack for 15 minutes before running a blunt knife around the sides and
inverting. Turn loaves to upright position and let cool completely. Wrap cakes
in plastic wrap for several hours, or overnight, before slicing. Cake will
stay fresh at room temperature when wrapped in plastic wrap for up to 3 days,
and freezes extremely well when wrapped in plastic wrap, then in aluminum
foil. Makes 2 loaves.;   Note: If you don't have dark honey on hand, use 1 1/2
tablespoons good quality light honey and 1/2 teaspoon molasses.;   -- From:
"Francine Prince's; New Jewish Cuisine" (G.P.; Putnam's Sons, $22.95)  </TEXT>
