<DESCRIPT>  VEGETABLE; FRUIT; FOOD; GUIDELINE; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WITHOUT question, this is the best time to buy local produce, because summer
and winter produce seasons have overlapped.;   There's barely enough room for
everything at produce stands, and what's there is exploding with color --
black globe eggplants, red and gold tomatoes, deep orange and green winter
squash.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SEASONS COLLIDE AT PRODUCE STAND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Produce; Chef Jesse Cool is co-founder of Flea Street Cafe and Late for the
Train in Menlo Park.; Additional information attached to the end of this
article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Savor it because the bulk of summer produce is nearing its end, and there
won't be many new and exciting crops from our growing area until next spring.
Local corn, grapes, melons, eggplant and summer squash will disappear within
the next few weeks.;   But as long as the weather stays warm, there will be a
wide variety of local organic tomatoes. The dry-farmed ones from Molino Creek
Farm I mentioned recently are sweeter this year than ever. Basil is still
prolific and peppers and chilies are flooding the produce stands.;   Fall
vegetables and fruits are just beginning. Baby root vegetables, tender young
fennel, winter squashes, pumpkins, root vegetables, cabbages, choys and the
vast arrays of leafy bitter and spicy greens will be at their peak as the
weather gets colder.;   A few fruits and vegetables are in their second
harvest and perfect for eating now.;   The second crop of fresh potatoes is
ready. My favorite, because people oooh and aah over them, are the bright
purple-fleshed Purple Peruvians. Irregularly shaped with black skin, they are
wonderful steamed or roasted. Forget peeling them or any tender-skinned
potato.;   Red-skinned baby Pontiacs, white-fleshed baking russets, golden
nutty Yellow Fins and, from Santa Cruz, sweet and nutty, finger-shaped
potatoes called ruby crescent or fingerlings may be eaten now or stored for
your holiday feasts.;   There is also a second harvest of berries from the
Watsonville area. Raspberries and strawberries are prolific and I think
sweeter this time around.;   There are many varieties of beans available too.;
  Snap beans will be around through November. Yellow wax, green and yellow
Romanos are coming from Pescadero. Baby Blue Lakes are still being harvested
at Webb Ranch in Menlo Park. When you can find them, purple runner beans (they
have glossy purple pods) should be eaten raw, because they turn dark green
when cooked.;   Interesting at their prime are fresh shelling beans. Look for
maroon-and-cream-skinned fresh cranberry beans. Although Phipps Ranch in
Pescadero specializes in dry beans, they occasionally have fresh shelling
beans for sale. They also give the kids big recycled cans to go out and pick
fruits and vegetables for themselves. You'll be amazed at what kids will eat,
beans included, if they pick their own.;   At Phipps, I've never seen so vast
a variety of dry beans. Just to look at them is worth the trip. Plus, it is
great for kids because it has a mini-aviary and zoo.;   Meaty and full-bodied
in flavor, fava beans take some time to remove from the pod, but they are
worth it. I simmer them until tender and then dress as I would fresh limas.;  
Tiny light green flageolets are a favorite in France and take barely any
cooking time. Butter and salt and pepper is all they need. I bet you won't be
able to stop eating them.;   Remember: Shelling beans such as cranberries and
favas must be removed from the pod before cooking.;   By mid-November, be sure
to have your dry storage bins full of apples, pears, potatoes, onions, garlic
and squash to use when little else is growing.;   I want to encourage you to
eat summer produce while it lasts. Freeze or can as much as possible now when
it's in its prime. This will ensure good-tasting treasures when the fresh
alternative is not in season.; FRESH FAVA BEANS WITH OLIVE OIL, LEMON AND
GARLIC; 1 pound fresh shelled fava or lima beans;  Water to cover; 1/4 cup
virgin olive oil; 3 to 4 cloves fresh garlic, chopped;  Juice of 1 or 2
lemons; 1/2 cup Italian parsley, coarsely chopped; 2 tablespoons fresh
oregano, chopped;  Salt and fresh ground pepper to taste;  Asiago, Parmesan or
aged Romano cheese;  In a covered saucepan, simmer beans in water until
tender, approximately 20 minutes. Drain off water and immediately toss with
all remaining ingredients. Serve warm as a side dish or room temperature as a
salad or appetizer. Garnish with thinly shaved aged Italian cheese.;   Note:
You can also coarsely chop the seasoned beans, add more olive oil and
seasonings and serve on slices of crusty baguette as an appetizer.; COOL TIPS;
(box) Seed and freeze yellow or red bell peppers. Thaw, drain and chop or
puree to add sweetness or zestiness to cold-weather sauces and stews. Drizzle
with a little olive oil, serve on top of a salad or with an antipasto.; (box)
Remove stems from fresh basil, blanch for 10 seconds, puree in food processor
and freeze in ice cube trays for later use.; (box) Core whole tomatoes, then
coat with olive oil and roast until the skin is brown. Freeze. Thaw and puree
for a tomato sauce that should knock your socks off.; (box) Remember those
old-fashioned desserts like pudding, tapioca and shortcake? Make them from
scratch. Top with fresh whole or pureed strawberries or raspberries and
whipped cream.  </TEXT>
