<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Chicago Tribune; Persimmon pudding is a quick -- but rich --
dessert for the holiday season, here garnished with champagne grapes.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  CAUTION: The holiday season can be -- or make that will be -- a dietary
hazard.;   With the onslaught of turkey and glazed ham, holidays play havoc
with good intentions so many of us have in mind. Cutting back on meat
consumption (and its quota of fat) becomes next to impossible.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VEGETARIAN MENU KEEPS FAT LEVEL LOW FOR HOLIDAYS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Vegetarian  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The vegetarian menu that follows is designed for when you feel as though
you've reached the meat eater's limit.;   The centerpiece is acorn squash
baked then filled with a mixture of couscous, vegetables, garbanzo beans and
dried fruit. Light and tasty, it offers a complete protein source.;   Many
salad possibilities balance the meal. You might select your favorite tossed
green salad. But wilted cabbage slaw is a fine option that is easy to make and
can be done ahead of time.;   For dessert, an old-fashioned steamed pudding
made from persimmons is clearly an indulgence. Or try a simple fruit compote
for a low-fat alternative.; SQUASH STUFFED WITH; COUSCOUS; 2 acorn squash; 2
dried ancho chilies, see note; 1 cup couscous; 3/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons
water; 1 bunch cilantro stems; 1 slice fresh ginger; 1 teaspoon cumin seeds;
1/2 teaspoon salt; 1 16-ounce can garbanzo beans, drained; 1/2 of a small tart
apple, unpeeled, finely diced; 1/2 small red bell pepper, finely diced; 4
green onions, thinly sliced; 1/4 cup dried apricots, finely chopped; 1/4 cup
chopped cilantro leaves; 2 tablespoons olive oil; 1 tablespoon fresh lemon
juice; 1 hot chili pepper, such as jalapeno, seeded if desired, minced; Salt,
pepper to taste;  Heat oven to 350 degrees. Cut squash in half crosswise and
scoop out all the seeds and stringy membrane. Add 1 inch of water to a 13- by
9-inch baking dish; crumble one ancho chili into the water. Put squash in pan,
cut side down. Bake until tender, 50 to 60 minutes, depending on size. Or, to
cook in a microwave oven, prepare as above, using a microwave-safe dish. Cover
tightly with plastic wrap and cook on high power until tender, about 15 to 18
minutes.;   Meanwhile, put couscous in a medium bowl and set aside. Heat 3/4
cup plus 2 tablespoons water, 1 ancho chili, cilantro stems, ginger, cumin and
salt to a boil in small saucepan; boil rapidly for 2 minutes. Pour through a
strainer over the couscous. Stir with a fork, cover tightly with plastic wrap
and let stand 10 minutes. Remove cover and separate grains with a fork.;  
Stir in remaining ingredients, including salt and pepper to taste.;  
Carefully trim a slice from the stem ends of the baked squash so they will
stand flat; divide couscous mixture among squash halves. Put trimmed stems of
squash over to make a cover. Return to oven and bake until heated through,
about 20 minutes. Or, place in microwave dish and cook on high power, loosely
covered, until hot, about 6 minutes. Makes 4 servings. Preparation time, 20
minutes; cooking time, 1 hour, 20 minutes;   Note: Dried ancho chilies are
available at Hispanic markets.; (hbox); WILTED CABBAGE SLAW; WITH ORANGE
SESAME; DRESSING; 1 small head green cabbage, about 1 1/4 pounds, thinly
sliced; 4 green onions, slivered; 1/4 cup minced fresh cilantro or parsley;
1/3 cup vegetable oil; 3 tablespoons seasoned rice vinegar or rice vinegar; 1
tablespoon honey mustard; 2 teaspoons sesame seeds; 1/2 teaspoon mustard
seeds; 1/2 teaspoon salt or to taste; Grated rind of 1 orange; 2 to 3
tablespoons orange juice; Red cabbage leaves or red leaf lettuce for serving; 
Mix cabbage, onions and cilantro in a bowl; set aside.;   Whisk oil, vinegar,
honey mustard, sesame and mustard seeds and salt together in a small pan. Heat
gently until the seeds begin to brown. Remove from the heat, add orange rind
and juice. Pour over cabbage mixture. Toss well. Salad can be served
immediately or covered tightly and refrigerated overnight. Toss well and
adjust the seasoning before serving on cabbage or lettuce leaves. Makes 4
servings. Preparation time, 10 minutes; cooking time, 3 minutes.; (hbox);
STEAMED PERSIMMON; PUDDING WITH DRIED; CRANBERRIES; 1/2 cup dried cranberries
or dried currants; 2 tablespoons dark rum; 1/2 cup finely ground butter cookie
crumbs (such as shortbread); 1/2 cup all-purpose flour; 1 1/2 teaspoons baking
soda; 1/2 teaspoon each: cinnamon, salt; Freshly grated nutmeg; 1 cup sugar;
1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened; 2 large eggs; 1 1/4 cups
persimmon pulp, see note; 1 tablespoon lemon juice; 1 cup chopped pecans;
Whipped cream;  Mix dried fruit and rum in a small plastic bag. Set aside for
several hours or overnight.;   Mix cookie crumbs, flour, baking soda,
cinnamon, salt and nutmeg in a bowl and set aside.;   Cream sugar and butter
with an electric mixer until light. Add eggs, one at a time, mixing well after
each addition. Add persimmon pulp and lemon juice and mix well. Add dry
ingredients and mix lightly; fold in pecans and soaked fruit with liquid.;  
Transfer to a buttered mold with a 6-cup capacity. A ring mold, pudding mold
or kugelhopf pan can be used. Cover tightly with foil, making sure that no
water will be able to get inside the mold. Secure in place with twine or a
heavy rubber band.;   Select a pot large enough to hold the mold and place a
steamer rack in the bottom. Pour in several inches of water then put the
pudding mold on the steamer rack. Cover the pan and heat to a boil. Reduce
heat and simmer gently 1 3/4 hours. Check periodically to make sure there is
water in the bottom of the pan.;   Carefully remove the mold from the pan.
Blot any water from the top of the foil then carefully remove the foil. Cool
in the mold for 10 minutes then invert onto a serving platter. Serve warm with
a dollop of whipped cream. Serves 10. Preparation time, 20 minutes; standing
time, several hours or overnight; cooking time, 1 1/2 hours.;   Note: Select
very ripe persimmons. Remove the stem end and scoop out the soft flesh from
inside the fruit. Mash with a fork or puree in a food processor.  </TEXT>
