<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; PRODUCT; BUDGET; PLANNING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN California, where we worship the Goddess of Fresh, the idea of eating
canned food may seem as sacrilegious as conducting high mass during a roller
derby match. But who doesn't come home from the supermarket without at least a
few canned goods in his environmentally correct canvas bag?;    More than 17
billion cans of food are produced in the United States each year, accounting
for 12 percent of grocery sales nationwide.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DON'T KICK THE CAN: A GOURMET GUIDE TO GROCERY
STAPLES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Consumer
Fourth Annual Supermarket Survey
Food Editor Sam Gugino is available for questions from 4-6 p.m. Wednesdays at
920-5539. Or you can write to him at the San Jose Mercury News, 750 Ridder
Park Drive, San Jose 95190.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Our favorites? In order of preference, they are soup, tuna, pasta, pork and
beans, corn, green beans, tomatoes, evaporated condensed milk, tomato sauce
and peaches, according to a survey by Selling Areas Marketing Inc. (SAMI).;   
Despite its popularity, canned food has traditionally gotten a bad rap for
nutrition when compared to fresh and frozen food.;    "That's because older
studies compared canned vegetables with produce that was just picked," says
Anne-Marie Farley of the Canned Information Council, "but when both were
analyzed after they had been cooked for consumption, the nutritional content
was comparable.";    Here are my 15 favorite canned foods and suggestions on
how to use them.;    (check) BEANS -- Canned beans can be just as effective as
dried beans at reducing cholesterol, but you don't have to wait hours while
they soak. Simply rinse off the surface starch and unnecessary salt that comes
with most canned beans.;    Chick peas are one of my favorites. Puree them
with sesame paste (tahini), garlic and lemon juice for hummus, the Middle
Eastern dip. Mix them with cannellini beans, scallions, parsley, lemon juice
and olive oil for a delicious bean salad that can be fortified with a topping
tuna for a main course. Or just sprinkle them on salads.;    Black beans make
a delicious Southwestern dip when pureed with minced canned jalapeno peppers,
ground cumin, chili powder, garlic and scallions. Make a quick bean soup with
canned chicken broth, crushed rosemary and canned lima beans in ham sauce (or
use plain lima beans and add bacon). Your signature chili with canned red
kidney or pinto beans is a snap with the addition of ground beef, onion,
garlic, tomatoes and that secret blend of spices.;    (check) TOMATOES -- Try
sauces from canned tomatoes with mussels and hot pepper over linguine; with
mushrooms and ground beef or turkey over fusilli; with sweet peppers and hot
Italian sausage on rigatoni; or with garlic and onion sauteed in olive oil
with a splash of red wine.;    Putting whole tomatoes through a food mill
eliminates the arduous task of removing seeds by hand and creates a
fresh-tasting puree that needs little or no thickening. Though plum tomatoes
are often thought to be best for sauces, many non-plum varieties are just as
good.;    Canned tomatoes are indispensible for soups and stews. Make a quick
winter gazpacho with canned tomatoes, canned diced green chilies, spicy V-8
juice and canned corn.;    (check) TOMATO and V-8 JUICES -- Jazz up either one
with Tabasco, Worcestershire sauce and horseradish for a delicious
non-alcoholic cocktail. Or just buy spicy V-8 and save yourself the trouble.
Both are good at stretching soups like gazpacho and as braising liquids in
lieu of stock or water. My wife's favorite low-cal dish is a stew of
vegetables in V-8 juice.;    (check) PEACHES -- Use them in cobblers, in
sauces for pork or chicken, in a baked fruit compote with a topping of
amaretti cookies, or in your own canned fruit salad (see recipe). They can be
combined with vanilla ice cream and pureed frozen raspberries for a quick
peach Melba or made into this no-fail dessert from "Super Meals from
Supermarkets" by Joe Famularo (Barron's, $12.95): Simmer 1/2 cup each of dark
rum and dark brown sugar in a pan until sugar dissolves. Drain a 29-ounce can
of sliced peaches and toss with the juice of one lemon in a bowl. Pour rum
sauce over and toss well. Serve in goblets topped with whipped cream and
nutmeg.;    (check) CORN -- Comparable to frozen and superior to out-of-season
fresh, canned corn makes a fine corn salad with pimentos, scallions and cumin.
I prefer to make my own succotash with frozen lima beans, bacon bits and fresh
chives. Also try it with okra, chopped tomatoes, scallions and green peppers
for an interesting side vegetable.;    Creamed corn is a favorite comfort food
that gives wonderful texture to cornbread made with a mix. It can be added to
canned New England clam chowder and sherry for a hearty soup. And corn pudding
is an easy affair when mixed with flour, baking soda, eggs and cream.;   
(check) ARTICHOKE HEARTS -- Buy the whole hearts in water rather than the
wedges marinated in oil, for greater versatility and calorie control. For
pizza and pasta toppings, they can't be beat. Natural partners include
prosciutto, olives, thyme, garlic, olive oil and pimentos or fresh-roasted red
bell peppers.;    Add some artichoke hearts to sauteed chicken breasts and
olives, then top with some grated Parmesan cheese and bake. Or make a quick
artichoke soup with some canned chicken stock and cream.;    (check) CLAMS --
When I can't think of what to eat for dinner that's quick and satisfying,
linguine with clam sauce often comes to mind. The only other ingredients you
need are garlic, olive oil, white wine and parsley. Use coarsely chopped clams
for pasta, minced clams with cream cheese for clam dip or sandwich spread and
whole clams for an easy paella (see recipe). Whole clams can also be the basis
for your own clam chowder or they can add punch to canned clam chowder.;   
(check) BEETS -- It's hard to justify the trouble of cooking fresh beets when
canned beets are so consistently good. I use pickled beets as part of an
antipasto platter for an easy cold meal on hot days. Plain canned beets are
the main ingredient of chlodnik, a refreshing cold soup with capers,
cucumbers, pickles, dill and sour cream. Add beets to salads, combine them
with minced onions for their own salad, or serve them as a hot vegetable
microwaved with orange juice, orange zest and sugar.;    (check) PUMPKIN PUREE
-- I defy you to tell the difference between fresh and canned pumpkin when
baked in a pie. But don't limit pumpkin puree to pie. A while back, I made a
delicious creme brulee with canned puree, eggs, cream and spices.;    Go
beyond desserts to use pumpkin puree in a soup with canned chicken stock,
cream and a dash of nutmeg. Add some pumpkin puree to a spoon bread recipe.;  
 (check) OLIVES -- Though I prefer the deeper flavors of cured olives, canned
ripe olives can be used in so many dishes, it's hard to keep them off the
list. Use them in tomato sauces for pasta and in pasta salads. Slice or
coarsely chop them for pizza and nachos. Mix them with cream cheese for
sandwich spreads or wrap them in thin slices of salami for hors d'oeuvres
coronets.;    Colossal olives can be stuffed with a horseradish cream for easy
hors d'oeuvres. Or they can be marinated as a condiment for submarine
sandwiches. Drain two cans of colossal olives. Mix 1/2 cup olive oil, 2
tablespoons red wine vinegar, 1 teaspoon dried thyme and 4 cloves peeled
garlic that have been crushed but left whole. Add the olives and allow to
marinate several hours or longer. Taste and remove the garlic when the flavor
suites you.;    (check) EVAPORATED OR CONDENSED MILK -- Evaporated milk is a
very good substitute for cream in many recipes and far less caloric. An old
favorite recipe involves breaded pork chops sauteed in a skillet until crisp
and almost done. Add evaporated milk and reduce to a thickened sauce. Serve
with garlic mashed potatoes that have also been made with evaporated milk.;   
Evaporated milk whips up like cream if it's well chilled. And it can be
reconstituted simply by adding water.;    Sweetened condensed milk is a key
ingredient in key lime pie (see recipe on 2C) and other desserts such as
cheesecake and rice pudding.;    (check) ANCHOVIES -- Anchovies are flavor
enhancers for more than Caesar salad. They add a subtle complexity to tomato
sauces for pasta, especially if gently sauteed with garlic in olive oil first.
Combined with garlic, olive oil and cream, they make a great dipping sauce
called bagna cauda for vegetables. Flavor braised lamb or veal shanks with
anchovies too.;    Make anchovy butter for anchovy toast hors d'oeuvres. Toss
anchovy fillets with freshly roasted sweet red peppers, olive oil and a touch
of garlic for an appetizer. And for a kinder, gentler flavor on pizzas, cut
them in bits and spread them underneath the tomato sauce before baking.;   
(check) CHICKEN BROTH -- Though I make my own, I'm never without a few cans.
In soups and stews you can hardly tell the difference from homemade. Use a
little chicken broth to deglaze the pan after you've sauteed some chicken,
veal or turkey breasts. If fats are a problem in your diet, "saute" onions or
garlic in chicken broth instead of oil or butter.;    Reduced sodium broths
are available for those on sodium-restricted diets. Be sure to remove the fat
before you use canned broth. Put the can in the freezer for 20 minutes to
allow the fat to rise to the top. Then skim it off.;    (check) PINEAPPLE --
Heat crushed pineapple pieces with some rum and brown sugar for a pound cake
or ice cream topping. Or combine crushed pineapple with pecans in a sweet
potato casserole.;    Use pineapple chunks in sweet and sour sauces for
chicken or pork. Drain chunks for fruit salads or eat the chunks by themselves
as a breakfast fruit. Pineapple rings can be used in an old-fashioned
upside-down cake.;    (check) CAPONATA -- As a kid, I used to eat this
"eggplant appetizer," as it is also called, right out of the can for a snack.
Made by Progresso, it's an Italian ratatouille. Use on antipasto platters or
as an appetizer with a topping of tuna.  </TEXT>
