<DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THANKSGIVING is a day to pay homage to the earth's bounty.;   For early
Americans, it was a day to humbly give thanks for the generosity of the summer
harvest, conferring reverence to the hard work spent preparing for the cold
months ahead. I've always been interested in how the settlers and the Indians
prepared for winter.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GIVING THANKS FOR FALL'S BOUNTY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article. Produce; Chef
Jesse Cool is owner/creator of Flea St. Cafe in Menlo Park.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In the spring and summer, they ate food from their gardens or nuts and
berries from the forests. They paid careful attention to preserving whatever
they could.;   Squash, potatoes, pears, apples and persimmons were carefully
secured in cold storage with the hope that there would be enough to last the
winter. Grains were dried whole or ground into flour.;   Root vegetables were
harvested until the earth froze. Then they were canned or stored. All this
completed, it was time to give thanks, eat what was available, and pray for an
early spring.;   This day epitomizes my feeling about honoring the seasonality
of fresh produce.;   While, unlike the early settlers, we won't starve if we
don't prepare for the winter, we still must do so. We're lucky this year
because summer lingered longer than usual.;   At the same time, fall crops
such as brussels spouts, quince and persimmons are abundant. For many people,
they are the stuff of traditional Thanksgiving dishes.;   Suggest organic;  
As usual, I recommend using organically grown produce. Brussels sprouts rank
high on the list of produce that is heavily sprayed.;   Some people wince when
they hear talk of brussels sprouts. Maybe this a partly because they've been
treated badly by generations of cooks. See my tips for advice.;   Brussels
sprouts can be eaten in any size, but they are best about the size of a silver
dollar. Both green and purple brussels sprouts are available in markets.
Although the purple are interesting-looking, I don't detect much difference in
flavor.;   You can purchase them on the stalk or in baskets. To prepare, cut
them off the stalk, trim a bit of the bottom off and make an "X" in the stem
to help with cooking.;   Avoid raw quince;   If you've ever eaten raw quince,
it made you wince.;   Quince is not at its best when eaten that way. When it
is cooked, it turns pink and has a delicious fragrance and flavor. Use your
favorite apple pie recipe and add sliced quince, but increase the amount of
sugar a bit.;   Persimmons are an often overlooked fall fruit. Primarily grown
here in California, they are not only beautiful, hanging like little lanterns
from naked tree branches, but they are a versatile delicacy.;   Fuyus, the
squat, round-shaped variety, are fine to eat raw. Or peel and substitute in
any apple recipe. At Flea St. Cafe we use them in pies, fruit crisps and in
salads with bitter greens and pungent cheeses.;   The oval, nearly
heart-shaped Hachiyas or American Persimmons are astringent and tannic until
ripe. They are best when the flesh is very soft and full of natural sugar.
They are commonly used in steamed puddings or spiced fruit breads.;   Now that
you've got some of fall's bounty in mind for the Thanksgiving feast, let's
talk about how to make the day less stressful.;   If you don't want to fuss
with a turkey or are a vegetarian who loves stuffing, fill partially cooked,
seeded winter squash with your favorite stuffing and serve as an entree or
side dish.;   Spread the workload;   Don't stress out trying to do too much.
Let guests bring a dish to contribute or keep your menu very simple. If all
you can accomplish is to create one recipe from scratch, acknowledge that and
feel good about it.;   With all this in mind, I'd also encourage you to
discuss the relationship between the settlers and the American Indians over
dinner.;   Moreover, this would be a perfect time and place to teach our
children that there is more to Thanksgiving than turkey and mashed potatoes.
More than many cultures today, American Indians continue to worship Mother
Earth for her favors that physically and spiritually feed us.;   This recipe
remains a traditional dessert at the All Hallows Thanksgiving Dinner, a
traditional pilgrim-style dinner held in Maryland. It is derived from The
Maryland's Way Cookbook. Get through the mindset that mashed potatoes can't be
sweet and you are in for a treat that originated in England and was brought to
this country by the original Pilgrims.; MARYLAND THANKSGIVING; WHITE POTATO
PIE; 1 pound baking potatoes; 2/3 cup butter; 1 cup sugar; 1 teaspoon salt;
1/2 cup heavy cream; 1/2 cup milk; 1/2 teaspoon baking powder; Juice of one
lemon; Zest of one lemon; 1/2 teaspoon fresh grated nutmeg; 1 1/2  teaspoon
vanilla; 4 eggs, beaten; 1 unbaked 8-inch pie crust;  Peel, cook and mash
potatoes. Add butter and after it has melted from the heat of the potatoes,
combine thoroughly. Whisk together sugar, salt, cream, milk and baking powder.
Add to potatoes with lemon juice, zest, nutmeg and vanilla, and beaten eggs.
Mix well.;   Fill pie shell with potato batter. Bake at 375 degrees until firm
and brown, 45 minutes to 1 hour. Serve with rum-scented whipped cream.; Don't
overcook brussels sprouts. Braise them in chicken stock or water until tender,
finish simply with garlic butter and a sprinkling of fresh chives and toasted
almonds and encourage people to try just one.; (box) Another alternative for
quince is to peel, slice, and preserve it in honey. This is delicious served
as a condiment with wild game or roast pork.; (box) Gardening expert Ros
Creasy recommends freezing and serving persimmons whole, peeling back the skin
and spooning out the flesh. Think of it as a low-calorie, intense sorbet.  </TEXT>
