<DESCRIPT>  VEGETABLE; FRUIT; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE BOUNTY of late summer is ours to enjoy.;   Impressive displays of locally
grown prime vegetables and fruits still can be found in most produce stands --
gorgeous tomatoes, crisp crimson plums, succulent red and golden raspberries,
glorious grapes and juicy summer melons.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CHILIES AND PEPPERS AND PEARS, OH MY!  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Seasonal Produce; See also related article on page 4D of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But there are new kids on the block -- pears, chilies and bell peppers.;  
(check) PEARS -- Many pears are picked before they ripen because they are
delicate and bruise easily. Because their flavors develop over time, pears
keep well in cold, dark storage -- although not necessarily a refrigerator.
Some of the heartier varieties can even be stored until early spring.;   Among
those that store well are the mild, white-fleshed Anjou pears. Their delicate
flavors actually come through better after two months in storage.;   Red or
green with amber spots, juicy sweet-fleshed Bartletts are also better when
ripened off the tree. They are excellent for fresh pear pie.;   Succulent
French and Italian butter pears will be ready to eat sooner than most. They
have a delicate light flesh and light brown skin and are a perfect match for
provocative brie-like cheeses and spicy nuts.;   It also best to pick tiny
Seckel pears, one of my favorites, before they are ripe and let them develop
their natural juices. Although not always pretty, they are one of the sweetest
pears, with spicy, rich tropical aromas.;   Store light-green and
russet-skinned Comice pears if they aren't ripe when on the stands. With their
rich, juicy flesh, they are best eaten raw. Bosc pears, with tender, aromatic,
smooth white flesh and long gourd-like necks, are fine for eating, baking and
drying. They are ready to eat when the skin is russet brown.;   Asian pears
tend to have thin skins and can come in odd shapes. For those who like a pear
with apple-like crispness, try one of the many varieties found at specialty
produce stands.;   (check) CHILI PEPPERS -- While they may often resemble each
other, bell peppers are sweet and chilies give off some degree of heat. There
are some chilies that are not hot, and they tend to have a deep, peppery
flavor.;   Stop by any Mexican produce stand or the Santa Cruz Flea Market. At
both sites, you are likely to find a phenomenal range of unusual chilies.;  
Look for a new one (at least to me) called a chilaca. It has a shiny
green-black skin, long, thin, pointed body like a pasilla and a mild, musky
flesh with hints of pepper. It is delicious on thinly sliced bread soaked with
olive oil.;   The horn-shaped golden Corno di Toro and the spherical tiny
cherry pepper are good examples of chilies that embody a sweet yet peppery
flavor.;   Poblanos are dark green with broad shoulders, coming to a point at
the tip. They are mild, meaty and perfect for chili rellenos.;   On the spicy
side, commonly found jalapenos -- red, yellow or green -- have great flavor
and impart plenty of heat.;   The hottest pepper I have ever tasted is the
tiny red Thai chili. Tepins are as big as a fingernail, but they are extremely
hot. Cayennes are red, long and slightly wrinkled.;   Thais, tepins, and
cayennes do not have much flavor, but they do create heat. All three dry
well.;   (check) SWEET BELL PEPPERS -- Red, gold and green peppers are the
sweet-tempered lookalikes to chilies.;   California Wonders, with thick skin
and meaty flesh, are sold green. But when they are ripe, they are sold as a
sweet red, yellow or sometimes black bell pepper.;   New on the market are
Gypsy peppers, red bells with tinges of gold. They are thick-fleshed but very
sweet, and are excellent eaten fresh or roasted. Pimentos are meaty and
perfect for roasting. Look for a Chocolate Pimento, a dark-skinned bell, at
Whole Foods Market in Palo Alto or the Palo Alto Farmers' Market.;   The
golden bells I've tasted this year are superb. Use them in any recipe that
calls for red bells or combine them for a confetti-like effect. Albino bells,
with their shiny white skin and light flesh, are very sweet and great for
salads.;   One person who makes excellent use of bell peppers is Lolly Font of
Los Altos, yoga teacher, devoted Italian mother of five and good friend to
many. She's also known for her passion for roasted sweet peppers. She roasts
them everywhere: on her outdoor grill, her indoor gas grill, in the broiler or
right over the gas burner. Rather than using a paper bag to steam off the
skins and to save the juices for other recipes, she tosses them into a covered
pot until they cool.; LOLLY FONT'S FAMOUS; ITALIAN ROAST PEPPERS; 4 large
sweet peppers (red, gold, or white); 4 tablespoons olive oil; 2 teaspoons
sliced fresh garlic; Salt and fresh-ground black pepper; 4 teaspoons fresh
parsley, chopped; 2 teaspoons fresh oregano, chopped; 2 tablespoons fresh
basil chopped; 6 ounces whole milk mozzarella;  Roast, peel and seed peppers,
reserving any juices. Slice or tear each pepper into 4 or 5 large pieces and
place in four individual baking dishes. Drizzle on each 1 tablespoon of olive
oil, 1/2 teaspoon sliced garlic, roasted pepper juices and salt and pepper to
taste.;   Chop together parsley, oregano and basil. Toss equal amounts on each
casserole. Top each with 1 1/2 ounces sliced mozzarella. Warm under broiler
until cheese is bubbly and beginning to brown. Serve with crusty Italian bread
for sopping up the juice.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; This is Organically Grown
Week, a time when the people who produce organic foods for a living want us to
ponder the chemicals used to grow food and consider that it can be done
another, safer way. Hidden Villa Farm on Moody Road in the Los Altos Hills
will conduct a workshop called "Organic: Is it really better for you?" on
Saturday from 10:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. A soup made of farm products will be
served. Admission is $10. Call (415) 949-8650.  </TEXT>
