<DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; ENTERTAINMENT; RECIPE; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THIS time of year, you want to welcome friends into your home. But for
practicality's sake, preparations must be streamlined to fit in with all the
other activities of the season.;   This menu is great for that, because it is
quick and much of it can be prepared in advance. The wild mushroom appetizer,
which may be used as a dip with crackers or mounded into the cleft of endive
leaves, is best made days or even one week before serving to fully develop the
flavors.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ENTERTAINING THOUGHTS
THINKING ABOUT HAVING SOME FRIENDS OVER? THIS MENU
GOES EASILY WITH THE HOLIDAY RUSH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Microwave  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The choucroute, an Alsatian dish that combines the influences of France and
Germany, is also easily made up to two days in advance and then reheated. To
reheat, cover and place in the microwave for 15 minutes.;   In fact, the only
two recipes that need to be made the day of serving are the potatoes and the
warm apple slices. Both are so simple they can be done when your attention is
spread thin.; WILD MUSHROOM PATE; 2 tablespoons unsalted butter; 1/2 cup
thinly sliced green onions; 1 pound fresh mushrooms (chanterelles or porcini
preferred, or 1/2 pound of these plus 1/2 pound domestic mushrooms), sliced; 2
tablespoons Madeira or brandy; 1/2 teaspoon salt; 1/2 teaspoon freshly grated
nutmeg; 1/2 cup sour cream or plain yogurt; 1/4 teaspoon freshly ground
pepper; 1/2 cup coarsely chopped hazelnuts; 2 tablespoons chopped chives or
parsley;  Combine butter and green onions in 2-quart microwaveproof casserole.
Microwave on high 2 minutes. Stir in mushrooms. Microwave, uncovered, on high
5 to 6 minutes or until mushrooms cook down and are slightly darkened.;  
Spoon mushrooms into bowl of food processor. Add Madeira, salt, nutmeg, sour
cream and pepper and process until smooth. Transfer mixture to bowl and fold
in nuts. Pack mixture into a crock, serving bowl or small new clay flowerpot.
Chill overnight or up to 1 week to develop flavors. Sprinkle with chives and
serve on croutons and/or crackers. Makes about 2 cups.; (hbox); CHOUCROUTE
GARNIE; 2 ounces slab bacon, rind removed and bacon cut into 1/2-inch cubes; 2
medium onions, thinly sliced; 2 cloves garlic, minced; 3 pounds sauerkraut,
rinsed; 1 1/2 cups chicken broth; 1 cup dry white wine; 1 large apple, cored
but not peeled, thinly sliced; 1/2 teaspoon caraway seeds; 1/2 teaspoon dried
thyme; 1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper; 1 bay leaf; 6 smoked pork chops; 6
links smoked bratwurst or kielbasa; Parsleyed Potatoes (recipe follows); 
Combine bacon, onions and garlic in 4-quart microwaveproof casserole.
Microwave on high 4 to 5 minutes or until onions are tender and bacon is
partially cooked. Stir in sauerkraut, broth, wine, apple, caraway seeds,
thyme, pepper and bay leaf. Cover tightly with lid or plastic wrap turned back
slightly on one side, and microwave on high 10 to 12 minutes or until liquid
is boiling. Stir.;   Transfer half the sauerkraut to a plate and arrange chops
and bratwurst over sauerkraut remaining in casserole, with thicker sections to
outside. Spoon sauerkraut back over meat. Cover with lid and microwave on high
10 minutes, then on medium 30 minutes or until meat is heated through and
flavor of dish developed. Let stand, covered, 10 to 15 minutes. Remove bay
leaf. Meanwhile, cook the potatoes. Serve with Parsleyed Potatoes and
pumpernickel bread. Makes 6 servings.; (hbox); PARSLEYED POTATOES; 2 pounds
small red potatoes, 1 1/2 to 2 inches in diameter, washed, with single strip
peeled around middle; 1/4 cup water; 1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley;  Combine
potatoes and water in 2-quart microwaveproof casserole. Cover tightly with lid
or plastic wrap turned back slightly on one side, and microwave on high 8 to
10 minutes or until potatoes are tender, stirring once. Let stand, covered, 3
minutes.;   Drain and arrange on platter with Choucroute Garnie. Sprinkle
potatoes with parsley. Makes 6 servings.; (hbox); WARM APPLE SLICES OVER ICE
CREAM; 1/4 cup unsalted butter; 1/4 cup brown sugar, packed; 4 ounces brandy;
1 tablespoon lemon juice; 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon (omit if serving
cinnamon ice cream); 4 tart cooking apples, peeled, cored, and cut into
1/4-inch slices; 1 quart vanilla or cinnamon ice cream;  Place butter in
9-inch glass pie plate and microwave on high 35 seconds to 1 minute to melt.
Stir in brown sugar, 2 ounces brandy, lemon juice and cinnamon. Stir in apples
and coat well with mixture. Cover with wax paper and microwave on high 6 to 7
minutes or until apples are tender.;   Scoop ice cream into 6 dessert dishes.
Pour remaining 2 ounces brandy in 1-cup glass measure. Microwave on high 15
seconds. Pour over apples and light with match. Spoon while still flaming over
ice cream. Makes 6 servings.; Marcia Cone and Thelma Snyder are the authors of
five books on microwave cooking, including "Microwave Entertaining," Simon and
Schuster.  </TEXT>
