<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO:  Vinaigrettes can be mixed to match almost any dish, salads to
desserts. (Color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN THE  thermometer starts pushing past 80, it's time to start thinking
about vinaigrettes to dress the myriad salads we'll be eating this summer.;   
Vinaigrette is the original and only true French dressing. Forget the orange
stuff that comes in a bottle and tastes like cough syrup.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BEST-DRESSED SALADS OF SUMMER WEAR VINAIGRETTES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article on page 8C  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In its simplest form, a vinaigrette contains only oil and vinegar, salt and
pepper. Indeed, as Cordon Bleu cooking instructor Richard Grausman points out,
"If the oil and vinegar used have excellent flavor, nothing else is needed."; 
  But with an endless selection of oils, flavored vinegars, fruit purees,
mustards, herbs and spices, vinaigrettes can be varied to suit almost any kind
of dish, from avocado and papaya salad to grilled fennel and leeks.;    Most
vinaigrette recipes call for three parts oil to one part vinegar. But
recently, Julia Child scoffed at that ratio.;    "A three-to-one-ratio is much
too strong of vinegar," Child said. "It should be more like five or six to
one, or just enough vinegar to remove the oily taste.";    In an effort to
reduce fat content of dressings, consumers have reduced oil to the point of
throat-gagging excess acidity. So how do you satisfy the dual gods of taste
and health? Keep in mind that a vinaigrette should coat food, not float it.
Most salads are badly overdressed. A healthy portion of green salad shouldn't
have more than two tablespoons of dressing, and some of that is going to be
vinegar and seasonings.;    Another way to combat excess vinaigrette is to
make sure greens and other foods are properly dried, so a minimum of dressing
is needed to adhere to them.;    Vinaigrettes can be swirled together in a
mixing bowl or shaken in a jar with a screw-top cap. The order in which you
mix a vinaigrette isn't usually important. But the late James Beard suggested
that only a small amount of vinegar should be added initially, and more added
later to suit individual tastes. "It is easier to add vinegar than to
counteract it," Beard reasoned.;    About the only time the order of
ingredients is important is when you make a creamy vinaigrette, which is
basically a thinned mayonnaise. To make a creamy vinaigrette, start with an
egg yolk and add oil gradually, as if making mayonnaise. Then add the
remaining ingredients. You can eliminate the egg if you use prepared mustard,
but the mustard must be at room temperature and the oil added very slowly.;   
And what about safety with that raw yolk? Make your creamy vinaigrette the day
before and the acids (vinegar or lemon juice) will kill any chance of
salmonella. In general, vinaigrettes, with or without egg yolks, should be
refrigerated and brought to room temperature for use.;    Here are some tips
for better vinaigrettes.;    Oil;  Like all things simple, vinaigrettes
require quality ingredients. It doesn't make sense to cut corners with
substandard oil and third-rate vinegar.;    (box) Olive oil: The primary oil
for vinaigrettes. Flavors and strengths can range from light and gently
perfumed to pungent and peppery. The oil you use should match the food it is
complementing. A heavy-duty olive oil won't wilt the flavor of mustard greens,
but it will overpower bibb or other mild lettuce.;    (box) Nut oils: Walnut
and almond oil are good for fruit and delicate salads. But buy nut oils in
small quantities and use them quickly, since they turn rancid faster than
other oils.;    (box) Sesame oil: Wonderful as an accent in Asian vinaigrettes
but it's strong stuff. Use it sparingly and make up the difference with peanut
oil.;    (box) Neutral oils: Though neutral oils such as safflower, canola and
corn oil are often called for in vinaigrette recipes, my feeling is "what's
the point?" They carry the same amount of calories as other oils, but none of
the flavor. Sometimes, however, you may want to emphasize the vinegar over the
oil and only a neutral oil will do. In that case, you might as well use
canola, which has the highest amount of heart-beneficial monounsaturated fat.;
   Vinegar;  (box)  Wine vinegars, white or red: Most commonly used in
vinaigrettes. But don't assume all are alike. Choose and shop for the kind you
like. Technically, sherry vinegar is a wine vinegar, but it's milder than most
wine vinegars. Try it with salads that have citrus fruit in them. I like to
use sherry vinaigrette on a salad of sliced oranges, with thin red onions and
oil-cured olives.;    (box) Asian vinegars: Mild rice wine vinegars don't have
to be used only in Asian dishes. Dark Chinkiang vinegar is also mild and has a
neat, malty taste.;    (box) Balsamic vinegar: It has a richness and natural
sweetness that make many vinaigrette combinations excel. Because it is milder
you can often use a higher percentage of it than other vinegars.;    (box)
Flavored vinegars: From raspberry to tarragon, they have their charms, but
they're more limited than most other vinegars.;    (box) Cider vinegar: Though
lost in the vinegar shuffle in the past few years, I like its light fruitiness
and somewhat mild flavor.;    Vinegar substitutes;  Lemon juice is the most
common substitute for vinegar, but you can also use it in combination with
vinegar. Lime juice is a good choice if you're doing a Latin or Asian-style
vinaigrette. Since you don't need a lot, there's no excuse for not using
fresh-squeezed juice.;    Other liquids;  A touch of wine gives a vinaigrette
sparkle. And if you use dry vermouth, you can eliminate adding herbs. Soy
sauce is a natural in Asian vinaigrettes. Nuoc mam or fish sauce can be used
to accent Thai or Vietnamese salads.;    Herbs;  Beard said that parsley and
chives were standard for all vinaigrettes. His other favorites were tarragon,
basil and dill. Child likes minced shallots. A good rule to follow is to have
one or two neutral herbs such as parsley and chives (or shallots or scallions)
and one other. Too many herbs confuse the taste buds.;    Other herbs to
consider are chervil, oregano, marjoram and thyme. Use fresh herbs whenever
possible.;    Spices;  Salt and pepper are the two most common seasonings, but
don't take them for granted. Kosher salt has a cleaner, less chemical taste
than most commercial salt. And there's nothing like fresh-ground black
pepper.;    Garlic adds wonderful flavor to vinaigrettes, but it can be
overpowering. Some recipes call for pounding it in a mortar with salt.
Delicious but pungent. For a less potent garlic accent, do what my mother
does. Add a whole, crushed clove of garlic to a vinaigrette several hours
before the dressing is used. Check the flavor every hour until the suggestion
of garlic is just where you want it. Then remove the clove. Or, you can roast
the garlic (one hour in a 325-degree oven) until it assumes a pleasing, nutty
flavor.;    Here are some more spice ideas: chili powder and ground, toasted
cumin for Southwestern vinaigrettes; finely minced lemon grass for Thai and
Vietnamese vinaigrettes; caraway seeds for a salad of shredded cabbage and
carrots; minced ginger with lime juice and scallions for Asian vegetables.;   
Et cetera;  Dijon mustard is a regular in my vinaigrettes, for its piquancy
and emulsifying properties. And don't forget all those flavored mustards such
as sweet and hot, dill, garlic.;    Try these too: capers, especially with
vinaigrettes for cold seafood or meat; pureed, kalamata or oil-cured olives to
brush on grilled bread; orange zest, especially with sherry vinegar; anchovy
paste for Caesar vinaigrettes on roasted red peppers.  </TEXT>
