<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Old standbys like sweet potatoes and cranberries; get new treatments as
accompaniments for the bird  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOOD SIDES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  SWEET POTATOES; AND APPLES; 2 pounds sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into
cubes; 1 1/4 cups orange juice; 1 1/2 tablespoons cornstarch; 1/2 teaspoon
ground cinnamon; 1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg; 4 tart apples, peeled, cored and
coarsely chopped; 1/4 cup coarsely chopped pecans or walnuts;  Steam the sweet
potato cubes over boiling water for 6 minutes, or cook on high in a microwave
for about the same length of time. The potatoes should be tender. Set the
potatoes aside.;   Combine the orange juice, cornstarch, cinnamon and nutmeg
in a large saucepan. Cook over medium heat, stirring constantly, until the
mixture begins to bubble and thicken.;   Stir in the chopped apples. Reduce
heat to a simmer and cook for 4 minutes. Add the nuts and cook a minute more.
Stir in the sweet potatoes and cook until warmed through. Serves 6 to 8.;
MINTED CARROTS; 2 pounds baby carrots, scraped (or use regular carrots and
slice); 4 cups water; 2 teaspoons sugar; 1 teaspoon salt; 1/2 cup butter; 6
tablespoons firmly packed brown sugar; 1 tablespoon cornstarch; 1 tablespoon
white creme de menthe; 1/4 cup fresh mint leaves, finely chopped;  Put the
carrots, water, sugar and salt in a saucepan. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat.
Cook for 15 minutes, or until carrots are tender. Drain, reserving about 1 cup
of the liquid.;   Melt the butter in a saucepan. Over low heat, stir in the
sugar and cornstarch. Cook for 1 minute, stirring constantly.;   Slowly pour
in the reserved liquid, stirring all the time. Cook over medium heat,
stirring, until thickened and bubbly. Stir in the creme de menthe and the
mint. Pour the sauce over the carrots and stir to coat. Serves 8.; CRANBERRY
MOLD; 2 packages unflavored gelatin; 1 cup cranberry juice; 3/4 cup sugar; 1
cup boiling water; 1 cup cranberries; 1 orange, quartered and seeded but not
peeled; 1 apple, quartered and cored but not peeled; 1/2 cup pecans; 1 8-ounce
package cream cheese; 1/4 cup sour cream;  Place the gelatin in the cranberry
juice. When the powder is well moistened, add the sugar and the boiling water.
Stir well. Pour into an attractive mold. Refrigerate until it starts to set.; 
 Put the cranberries, orange, apple and pecans in a food processor. Coarsely
chop. You may need to do this in batches. Stir the fruit and nuts into the
gelatin. Refrigerate.;   When the gelatin is set, place the cream cheese and
sour cream in a food processor (or use an electric mixer). Mix well. Spread
with a spatula over the gelatin. Loosen gelatin in hot water and invert onto
plate. Serves 8.; BRAISED CHESTNUTS; 1 pound large fresh chestnuts; 2 cups
chicken stock or broth; 1 celery stalk, broken into pieces; Salt; Freshly
ground pepper; 1 to 2 tablespoons unsalted butter;  Put chestnuts in a medium
saucepan and add water to cover by about 1 inch. Bring to full boil; cook 1
minute. Remove a nut with slotted spoon and peel by first cutting base and
pulling off outer skin, then pulling and scraping off inner skin. Continue
with remaining nuts, removing from water one by one.;   Put chestnuts in a
medium saucepan with stock, celery, salt and pepper. Bring to a boil, reduce
heat to low, cover, and simmer about 15 minutes, or until chestnuts are just
tender when pierced with point of a knife. Do not overcook or chestnuts will
fall apart. Uncover and leave in liquid until ready to use. (Chestnuts can be
kept in their liquid, covered, up to 2 days in refrigerator.);   To serve,
reheat chestnuts in their cooking liquid in covered saucepan over low heat.
Discard celery and cooking liquid. Add butter to chestnuts and shake over low
heat until blended. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot. Makes 4 servings.;
-- From "Fresh From; France: Vegetable Creations"; by Faye Levy (Dutton);
BRUSSELS SPROUTS GRATIN; 1 pound brussels sprouts; 2 ounces bacon (about 4
strips); 1 tablespoon unsalted butter for greasing dish, plus 1/4 cup, cut
into pieces; 1/2 cup whipping cream; 1 tablespoon fresh bread crumbs;  Prepare
brussels sprouts by cutting thin slice off root end of each and then cutting
an "X" in that end so it cooks evenly inside and out. Blanch sprouts in large
pan of boiling, salted water until tender-crisp, about 5 minutes. Drain.
Refresh in ice cold water and drain again. (Do not let sprouts remain in cold
water for more than 1 minute or they will become soggy.);   Saute bacon until
limp but not crisp. Drain bacon and coarsely chop. Mix together sprouts and
bacon and spoon mixture into buttered gratin dish. Pour cream over top and dot
with bread crumbs and butter pieces. Bake at 400 degrees 20 minutes or until
hot. Makes 4 to 6 servings.; GREEN BEANS WITH; MUSHROOMS; 2 pounds green
beans, trimmed; 1/2 pound shiitake or regular white mushrooms; 4 tablespoons (
1/2 stick) butter; 1/4 cup walnut or vegetable oil; 1/2 teaspoon salt; Freshly
ground black pepper to taste; 1/2 cup toasted chopped walnuts for garnish; 
Drop the beans into a large pan of lightly salted boiling water and simmer
over medium-low heat for about 4 minutes, or until barely tender. Drain into a
colander, then run cold water over the beans to stop the cooking and to help
retain the color. Set aside. Remove the stems from the shiitake mushrooms and
discard. (If using regular white mushrooms, trim the stems, but leave them
attached to the caps.) Rinse the caps and pat dry on paper towels. Cut the
caps (or the whole white mushrooms) into 1/4-inch slices and set aside. (May
be done ahead up to this point.);   Combine the butter and oil in a large
skillet or wok over medium-high heat. When it is hot, add the beans and
mushrooms and cook, stirring and tossing, until the mushrooms are limp and the
beans are hot and tender-crisp. Add the salt and a liberal amount of pepper.
Turn into a warm serving bowl and sprinkle with the walnuts. Makes 8
servings.; -- From "The Thanksgiving; Cookbook" by Holly Garrison; (Macmillan
Publishing Co.)  </TEXT>
