<LEADPARA>  THE pungent scent of the six "hot spices of Christmas" are as much a part of
the holiday as the perfume of the pine.;   They are cinnamon, cloves, ginger,
nutmeg, mace and allspice, according to McCormick/Schilling, a major U.S.
spice producer.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOW BEST TO USE HOLIDAY SPICES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     When buying spices, remember that whole spices keep longer than their
ground counterparts. Although spices do not spoil, they should be checked once
a year for potency. Once opened, they lose flavor and aroma.;   Never store
spices near a heat source or near strong, direct light. To test for freshness,
give the container a sniff. If the aroma greets you without having to bury
your nose in the container, the spice is still in peak condition.;   Here's a
spice primer, with some tips on how to use them in holiday foods:;   (box)
Despite its name, allspice, often called Jamaican pepper, is the berry of an
evergreen tree, native to the Caribbean. The flavor is a combination of
cinnamon, nutmeg and cloves, which accounts for its name. Any or all three may
be substituted for allspice in a recipe. If a recipe, such as fruitcake, calls
for allspice and nutmeg, cloves and cinnamon, it's often wise to cut back on
the cloves to avoid overpowering the food.;   The Scandinavians popularized
allspice, using it in marinades to pickle fish. While the whole berries are
good in marinades, tomato sauce and other liquids, they do not soften and
should be set aside when eating. Ground allspice will color a food, so use it
only when color is not a factor.;   (box) Cinnamon is the bark of a tree,
which is peeled and dried in the sun. In this country, what we call cinnamon
is really cassia, a member of the cinnamon family. True cinnamon is sold in
Mexico and has a milder flavor than cassia.;   Use cinnamon sticks to stir hot
chocolate or other creamy hot drinks; or use to flavor hot punches. Ground
cinnamon is a natural in apple pie, sprinkled on grapefruit or French toast,
added to stewed or baked fruit and coffee cakes.;   (box) Nutmeg and mace
commonly are grouped together because they both come from the nutmeg tree.
Nutmeg is the seed of a fruit that looks something like an apricot. Mace is
the orange-red lacy covering of the seed.;   Although nutmeg is stronger and
darker in color than mace, they can be interchanged. However, many people find
the lesser known mace to have a more pleasing flavor. Try substituting mace
for nutmeg in chocolate dishes.;   Sprinkle either or both on eggnog; add to
spiced nuts, liver pate, cocktail meatballs or creamy seafood.;   (box) Cloves
are the unopened bud of a tree. If the bud opens to a flower, the "crop" is
ruined. Permanent scaffolding is usually is placed around the tree, so pickers
can pick the buds daily.;   Use a whole clove to flavor the water when cooking
beets or in a spice pouch when flavoring a hot punch. Use ground cloves in
spice cakes and cookies and in barbecue sauce. Whole cloves increase in flavor
as the dish stands, so when refrigerating the food overnight, you may want to
remove the cloves.;   (box) Ginger was an ancient Oriental spice, one of the
earliest Oriental spices known to Europeans. It is the rhizome, a root-like
structure of a plant. It is well-known in its knotty form as the stuff of
Chinese food and in its ground form as the major ingredient in everyone's
favorite Christmas cookie.;   Crystallized or candied ginger has been cooked
in a sugar syrup.;   Ginger will complement chicken, pork and carrots. Add a
dash of ginger to the mayonnaise when making Waldorf salad. Use in pumpkin and
apple pie, sweet potato dishes and syrup for fruit punches.  </TEXT>
